<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stocks Up 1.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KARACHI, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi share market,
expecting a further cut in interest rates, Wednesday witnessed a
buying wave that gave a surge of 32.28 points, or 1.61 percent, to
the 100-share index to 2,034.61 points.
</P>
<P>
The market which was gradually losing charms during the last
few days, reversed the tide Tuesday when the index stayed on a
steady course upwards breaking the psychological barrier of 2,000-
point once again.
</P>
<P>
The buying euphoria continued Wednesday morning, pushing the
index higher on a turnover of 409.191 million shares against 296.
798 million shares traded on Tuesday. The market capital also rose
to 514.49 billion rupees (9.89 billion U.S. dollars) from 50.58
billion rupees (9.74 billion dollars) of the previous day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Order Halt to Kabul's Open Currency Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
militia Wednesday announced the closure of "open market" in
capital Kabul for "some period" in a bid to stabilize the
depreciating Afghan currency, Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken when the Afghani fell to all-time low.
On Wednesday, one U.S. dollar was being changed for 75,000
Afghanis in Kabul's Sara-e-Shahzada market, forcing the Taliban
authorities to halt the business.
</P>
<P>
AIP said the Islamic militia also banned carrying Afghani from
opposition-held northern Afghanistan and from neighboring
countries into Taliban-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an unnamed Taliban official as accusing the
opposition of having been pouring in billions of fake Afghanis
into Taliban-ruled areas to destabilize the currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
