<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia on Wednesday lodged its "strongest
protest" against a decision made earlier by leaders of the
European Union (EU) to tighten its current financial sanctions
against the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Slamming the decision as "unilateral and illegal," the Yugoslav
Foreign Ministry said in a statement that it will pose a serious
threat to the life of the country's poor, and is completely in
violation of international law and the EU's established policies.
(Yugoslavia-EU-Protest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian police said Wednesday morning that they have
arrested a 15-year-old cyber attacker with a screen name of "
Mafiaboy", who is believed to be linked with attacks against
famous Web sites such as Yahoo!, Ebay and Amazon.com in February.
</P>
<P>
Police nabbed the boy in Montreal at the weekend and charged
the teen hacker on Monday. The real name of the boy was not
disclosed according to Canadian law. (Canada-Hacker-Arrested)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- A preparatory meeting for the inter-Korean summit will
be held Saturday at the truce village of Panmunjom at 10 a.m.
local time (0100GMT).
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang Wednesday informed Seoul of accepting its proposal on
the preparatory meeting for the summit which is scheduled for
Pyongyang on June 12-14. (Seoul-Pyongyang-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian Federation Council, upper house of
parliament, Wednesday ratified the Russian-U.S. second-phase
Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START II) by a vote of 126
against 18 with six abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Russian State Duma, lower chamber of parliament,
passed the treaty on April 14 by 288 votes in favor with 131
against and four abstentions. (Russia-START II-Approval)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema has resigned following heavy losses of his center-left
coalition in Sunday's regional elections.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema's resignation was accepted Wednesday evening by
President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, officials said. (Italy-PM-
Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel on Wednesday filed a complaint with the
Grapes of Wrath Monitoring Committee (GWMC), accusing Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas for their Katyusha attacks against Israel's
northern civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military said that several long-range 122-millimeter
Katyusha rockets fired by Hezbollah guerrillas hit western Galilee,
northern Israel, Tuesday afternoon. One of them hit the road at
the entrance to a settlement, which damaged an electricity
transformer and caused a blackout in the region for several hours.
(Israel-Hezbollah-Complaint)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's lower house of parliament on Wednesday
appointed former prime minister Sergei Stepashin as head of the
country's Audit Chamber.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was approved by a vote of 309-29 with 10
abstentions in the State Duma, the Interfax news agency reported.
( Russia-Stepashin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin said in Ankara
on Wednesday that the Sino-Turkish relations have advanced
smoothly since they established diplomatic ties in 1971, thanks to
the joint efforts of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should further their cooperation in various
fields to promote bilateral relations in an all-round way, Jiang
said at a luncheon hosted by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
in his honor. (Turkey-Jiang-Ecevit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The Belgian Royal Academy of Medicine is advising
against the import of blood and blood products from Britain, local
media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The medical agency said anyone who spent longer than six months
in Britain between 1980 and 1996 should also not donate blood. (
Belgium-Britain-Blood)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The deteriorating economic and political
situation in Zimbabwe has affected the mood of investors in South
African markets, said Governor of the South African Reserve Bank
Tito Mboweni on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the Zimbabwe situation is adding to some negative
mood and sentiment, and the quicker they resolve their issues
there, the better for us," he told members of the National
Assembly's finance portfolio committee. (SAfrica-Zimbabwe-Market)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Three children, 8, 9 and 13 years of age, have
confessed to placing a concrete block on train tracks on the
Charleroi-Namur line, causing a head-on train collision Tuesday in
which the driver of one train was killed.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported Wednesday that the concrete block was laid
on a crucial switch and caused one train to derail. An oncoming
train crashed into it at high speed. Three people were seriously
injured and some 20 others suffered light injuries. (Belgium-
Train-Guilt)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- All 131 people on board the Air Philippines Flight
541 were killed when the jet crash-landed Wednesday morning in
Samal Island near Davao City in the southern Philippines, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine National Disaster Coordinating
Council (NDCC), the Boeing 737-200 with 124 passengers and seven
crew members on board crashed at around 07:20 local time (23:20
GMT, Tuesday) in Mount Caanlangan of Samal Island, some 1,000
kilometers south of Manila. (Philippines-Plane Crash-Writethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO - Sri Lanka's Tamil Tiger rebels have launched a fresh
offensive against military positions along a strategic highway in
northern Jaffna to mark the fifth anniversary of what is known as
Eelam War III which fell on Wednesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued from their office in London late on
Tuesday, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels said
that fierce fighting had erupted in the Thenmarachchi sector of
the peninsula. (Sri Lanka-Rebels)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The 13 Lebanese detainees who were freed by Israel
and delivered to the International Red Cross Organization have
arrived in Lebanon Wednesday afternoon, People's Sound radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Lebanese, imprisoned by Israel for more than a decade
without trial, were held by Israel as bargaining chips for
exchanging the missing Israeli air force navigator Ron Arad,
allegedly held by Lebanese anti-Israel resistance movements. (
Lebanon-Detainees-Israel) 
</P>
</TEXT>
