<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Lebanese Presidents Discuss Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
discussed on Thursday with visiting Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
the Middle East peace process, particularly Israel's plan to
withdraw from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders underscored the necessity that the (Israeli)
withdrawal be carried out in line with (the United Nations Security
Council) resolution 425," Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-
Sharif told reporters after a one-on-one meeting between Mubarak
and Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
"The two presidents also stressed the necessity of respecting
Lebanon's territorial waters, airspace and sovereignty over the
whole Lebanese national land," el-Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and set up a self-proclaimed
security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with the excuse to protect
its northern areas from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Israel formally notified United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan that it will withdraw from Lebanon by July under
the U.N. Security Council resolutions 425 and 426, even without an
agreement with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Lahoud also reviewed the Syrian-Israeli and
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, el-Sharif said. They reiterated
the importance of complying with the land-for-peace principle, the
relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions and the internationally
recognized borders of Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Lahoud urged the Palestinians and Israel to push
forward their negotiations, reiterating that resolving the
Palestinian problem holds the key to a comprehensive, durable and
just peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud arrived here earlier in the day for a two-day visit, his
first since assuming power in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
