<HEADLINE> Peru's Opposition Presidential Candidate to Meet U.S. Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Peru's opposition presidential
candidate Alejandro Toledo, who came out second to President
Alberto Fujimori in the April 9 election, will meet next Monday
with U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Toledo said Wednesday night, before leaving with his family for
Miami, that he will talk next week about the incidents in the
Peruvian electoral process with members of the White House and
representatives of independent organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Peru Possible coalition candidate also foresees a meeting
with a group of U.S. investors and some experts on the situation
of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Toledo will meet the Council of Businessmen, where he will
describe some points of his economic program.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian politician agenda includes an exposition before an
influential private institution, the Americas Society, with
headquarters in New York City.
</P>
<P>
Toledo and Fujimory will vie for the Peruvian presidency in a
second electoral round foreseen for the first week of June,
because they obtained the biggest number of votes in the last
election, but none of them got the absolute majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
