<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Economy to Grow over 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government is
expecting an average real growth of the national economy above
four percent in the next three years, said Thursday Finance
Minister Pedro Malan.
</P>
<P>
Malan told Radiobras that Brazil has a very concrete
possibility of combining a sustainable growth with a dropping
inflation, that will reach six percent this year and four percent
the next.
</P>
<P>
He said that this sustainable growth of the economy will favor
the creation of jobs, as well as a bigger expansion of consuming,
sales, investments and exports.
</P>
<P>
Malan said that this target will be reached unless there is a
big international disaster or that the country goes through a big
mistake.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the interest rate, he said that it will be shrinking
in the next months and even years, explaining that the drop of the
rates depends on the evolution of the international domestic
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The minister refused to forecast a figure for trade surplus of
this year, alleging that he is concerned with the trend and the
direction, not with figures.
</P>
<P>
He said that the devaluation of the real, the Brazilian
currency, has "long term effects" in the rise of exports and in
the Brazilian domestic production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
