<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British, Irish PMs Cautiously Optimistic on N.Ireland Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The British and Irish prime
ministers Thursday cautiously expressed "confidence" over
achieving a breakthrough in the stalled Northern Ireland peace
process.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish Premier Bertie
Ahern said they saw a glimmer of progress in the peace process but
admitted they had yet to achieve a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from Downing Street after two hours of talks with Tony
Blair, Ahern said that while there had been "some progress" in
discussions, there had not been any "fundamental breakthrough."
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation between the British and Irish governments is
excellent. It does give me confidence. On the other side of Easter,
we can make progress," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that it was "not going to be easy."
</P>
<P>
"We don't have a simple resolution," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting was the second in three days between the two
leaders. It came as the Irish Republic Army (IRA) issued its
Easter message that it wanted a "permanent peace" but that the
British government was still prosecuting a "war" against
republicans.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Belfast earlier this week, Blair met
representatives of all the main parties and described discussions
as "good and constructive." But he warned against false
expectations of an imminent breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
"There are possibilities, but it is important we don't raise
people's expectations too highly before we have really been able
to explore what those possibilities might be," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Many people in Northern Ireland see the next few weeks as make-
or-break for the British province's landmark Good Friday peace
accord, signed about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 pact envisaged complete disarmament of the IRA by May
22 this year. Some analysts said its credibility will be ripped to
shreds if not one gun is handed over by that date.
</P>
<P>
Britain suspended Belfast's fledgling home-rule joint
government in February because it said the IRA had shown no
commitment to disarm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
