<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Meets with Arafat on Israeli-Palestinian Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright held talks on Thursday with Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat over the virtually stalled Israeli-
Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Albright met Arafat over lunch at her Georgetown residence. The
contents of their discussions were not disclosed but State
Department spokesman James Rubin said that the United States was
prepared to play a more active role in the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations as the September deadline for a final status
agreement was drawing nearer.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone agreed that we will play a more involved role by
being at the table, trying to be creative, trying to help each
side figure out what its needs are," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
President Bill Clinton wanted to use the face-to-face talks to
make sure what Washington could do to help Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations move toward a framework agreement and then a final
status agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I think the president thought it would be useful and effective
to use this time to meet directly to see what we can do to keep
these (talks) on track," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Clinton held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to try to renew momentum in the negotiations between Israel
and the Palestinians as the target date for a framework agreement
in May is drawing nearer while gaps still remained wide between
the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said both Israel and the Palestinians were facing very
difficult issues, saying that "they have a very tight time line."
</P>
<P>
The second round of Bolling Air Force Base negotiations between
Israeli and Palestinian delegations ended last weekend with an
exchange of position papers on the framework agreement but no
evidence of substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say that Washington is trying to help bridge the
gaps but it has not reached the stage of proposing compromises.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said on Monday that he would take some "positive ideas"
to the White House, and considered his trip to Washington "a
crucial and basic step to push the peace process forward."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian cabinet minister Hassan Asfour on Tuesday held out
little hope for a breakthrough when Arafat meets Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing new to add." he said. "There is no place for
more flexibility. We were the party which made a historical
concession in 1993 and not the Israelis."
</P>
<P>
1993 was the year of the Oslo accords between Israel and the
PLO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
