<HEADLINE> Rwandan Genocide Suspect Pleads Not Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Jean Bosco Barayagwiza, a key
genocide suspect, has refused to plead guilty or not guilty to the
charges brought against him by the prosecutor at the International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) based in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwanda News Agency on Thursday, Barayagwiza,
former director of political affairs in Rwandan foreign ministry
and one of the founders of the extremist Radio Television Libre
des Mille Collines (RTLM), was accused of genocide, crimes against
humanity and serious violation of the Geneva Conventions.
</P>
<P>
Barayagwiza also refused on Wednesday to cooperate with the
defense counsel, assigned to him by the Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Despite his objections, the presiding judge Navanthem Pilly
entered a plea of not guilty to each of the three counts.
</P>
<P>
Upon the ICTR Chief Prosecutor's request, the Appeals Chamber
reversed its earlier decision to release Barayagwiza on procedural
grounds.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a joint trial of ring leaders of the
Rwandan hate media campaign is scheduled to start on June 5 at
the ICTR and the accused include Ferdinand Nahimana, former
director of RTLM , Ngeze Hassan, former editor of the extremist
Kangura News Paper and Jean Bosco Barayagwiza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
