<HEADLINE> Resumption of Syrian-Israeli Talks Still Possible: EU Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Mideast
special
envoy Miguel Moratinos said here Thursday that there is still a
chance to revive the Syrian-Israeli peace talks that have been
stalled since January 10.
</P>
<P>
"Although the road to the Syrian-Israeli peace is not smooth, I
believe there is still a chance to resume the talks. We must find a
way of reviving the talks," Moratinos told reporters after meeting
Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that he felt a real desire to resume the talks
during his meetings with Syrian, Israeli and U.S. officials. "There
are some points that need to be clarified before the resumption but

we hope that this will be done soon," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks were resumed in Washington in
December, 1999, after a four-year freeze but entered a blind alley
on
January 10 due to the disputes over the Golan Heights, water
resources and security issues.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos termed his talks with Shareh as successful and
fruitful. He said he conveyed to the Syrian official the EU
commitment to help the concerned parties establish a just,
comprehensive and lasting peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The differences between Syria and Israel focus mainly on the
issue of Tiberias Lake as the former wants to restore sovereignty
over the northeastern coast of the lake in line with the borders of
June 4, 1967, while the latter claims full sovereignty over the
lake.
</P>
<P>
However, there are some proposals of launching joint tourist
projects between the two countries around the lake or declaring it
a natural reserve and permitting access to it by the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy arrived here Thursday morning on a short visit to
Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
