<HEADLINE> Egypt Finds Greco-Roman Fortress in Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- French and Egyptian archaeologists
have found the remains of a Greco-Roman fortress town built along
an ancient caravan route in the Egyptian desert, a senior
antiquities official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The site was discovered on the ancient route linking Qaft, near
the Nile south of Cairo, and Berenice, further southeast near the
Red Sea, said Mohammed al-Saghir, director-general of the Southern
Sector of Egypt's Supreme Council of Antiquities.
</P>
<P>
The team also found nearby a small stone temple, a collection of
bronze coins, the head of a statue, and pottery shards, as well as
tablets bearing Greek inscriptions from private letters or legal
documents, Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The temple walls contain Greek inscriptions painted in red, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The papyrus, textiles and leather found at the site prove the
town and fortress were busy because on the one hand they served the
caravans and on the other they profited from the eastern desert's
mines and quarries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The remains that were discovered show the precision and sense
of order of the town which was among 13 others built on this
route," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
