<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Khartoum Reopened after 2-Year Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Embassy in Khartoum
resumed its function with the arrival of Charge D'Affaires Donald
Titlbom here from Nairobi last Saturday after a two-year
suspension,
the Sudanese News Agency (SNA) reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Consul Donald Mulligan will arrive here from Cairo early
next week and an administrative attache is due to arrive here from
Nairobi, capital of Kenya, soon, SNA added.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese Foreign Ministry issued visas to the three U.S.
diplomats recently.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official will administer some diplomatic and
administrative functions such as issuing U.S. visas to Sudanese
nationals who should, in the past, travel to Egypt first to get the
visas, SNA noted.
</P>
<P>
In February 1996, Washington closed its embassy in Khartoum
and moved its staff to Nairobi as a result of the U.N. imposed
sanctions on Sudan due to the latter's refusal to extradite the
suspects of an attempt on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's life
in
1995.
</P>
<P>
In September, 1997, Washington sent the staff back to Khartoum.
However, the diplomatic activity was suspended anew in August
1998, after the double bomb attacks against U.S. embassies in
Nairobi and Dar El-Salam which claimed 224 lives including 12 U.S.
nationals. 
</P>
