<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2000 NPT Review Conference to Be Held at U.N. Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The 2000 Review Conference
of the Parties to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear
Weapons(NPT) will meet at the United Nations in New York from
April 24 to May 19, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The previsions of the Treaty, which opened for signature in
1968 and went into force in 1970, envisage a review of the
operation of the Treaty every five years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Jayantha Dhanapala, U.N.Under-Secretary-
General for the Disarmament Affairs, said "The treaty is the most
important legal instrument in the area of disarmament. It is
commonly acknowledged to be the cornerstone of the nuclear non-
proliferation regime."
</P>
<P>
"This particular conference is more significant because not
only the first in the 21st century, but it is the first in the
strengthened review process that was inaugurated in 1995,' he said.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 Review Conference is the first to meet following the
Treaty's indefinite extension at the 1995 Conference.
</P>
<P>
States Parties will examine the implementation of the Treaty's
provisions since 1995, taking into account the decisions on the
principles and objectives for nuclear non-proliferation and
disarmament and the strengthening of the review process for the
Treaty as well as the resolution on the resolution on the Middle
East adopted at the 1995 Conference.
</P>
<P>
The NPT is a landmark international treaty whose objective is
to prevent the spread of nuclear weapons and weapons technology,
to promote cooperation in the peaceful uses of nuclear energy and
to further the goal of achieving nuclear disarmament and general
and complete disarmament.
</P>
<P>
By January 2000, a total of 187 parties had joined the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EAC Committed to Regional Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The main task of the
re-launched East African Community (EAC) is to stimulate economic
growth and alleviate poverty in the region, the outgoing chairman
of the permanent tripartite commission Eriya Ketegaya of Uganda
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the commission's 15th meeting held in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha, where the secretariat of the regional
bloc is located, the chairman said the objective should be a
historical mission and the new community offers the best
opportunity to realize it.
</P>
<P>
The EAC focus should be in directing energies in uplifting the
standards of poor people in the region, stressed Ketegaya when
handing over the annual rotating tripartite chairmanship to
Kenya's Minister for Tourism, Trade and Industry Nicholas Biwott.
</P>
<P>
Ketegaya, who is also Uganda's First Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister for Foreign Affairs, also asked the EAC to address
concerns of low levels of investment and production as well as the
inadequate infrastructure development in the three member
countries of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
"Low levels of domestic and foreign investment in the region
continues to hamper the stimulation of our economies to the
desired level," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ketegaya also underlined special importance of involving the
private sector in the EAC integration process, saying that "they
are indispensable partners in the process, they will constitute a
major factor in the region' s economic growth and development."
</P>
<P>
On program implementation, the Uganda Deputy Prime Minister
exhorted member states to select a list of priority programs to be
realized within a time frame.
</P>
<P>
"This is because any attempt to implement all the provisions of
the treaty may prove counter-productive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should bear in mind the resource constraints and our desire
to move steadily and surely."
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania signed a treaty last
November forming an East African economic bloc, reviving a
regional coalition that collapsed 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The new treaty recreates the former regional East African
Community, renaming it the East African Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The former bloc collapsed in 1977, partly because of a
divergence of economic policies carried out in the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Today, they are all pursuing free market economies and policies
of privatization, factors they hope will contribute to success
this time around. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
