<HEADLINE> Uganda Appeals to EU for Lifting Ban on Fish Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has appealed to the
European Union (EU) for lifting the year-long ban on its fish
exports to the international market because they are now safe for
human consumption, Radio Uganda reported here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is committed to the quality and safety of its fish for
local and international markets, said Fred Mukisa, minister of
state for fisheries, when discussing with EU ambassadors
accredited to Uganda on the process of its re-entry into the
international market.
</P>
<P>
Mukisa lamented the sharp decline of foreign exchange earnings
due to the tough ban, saying that it also affected some 700,000
people who depend on fishing for their living.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted French Ambassador Rene Roudaut as saying that
the fish ban would soon be lifted because of the steps the
Ugandan government has taken to ensure safe fish products.
</P>
<P>
EU, the largest destination of Ugandan fish exports, slashed a
ban on Uganda's fish products in early 1999, which costs the
country almost one million U.S. dollars a week. The fish export
is the second largest foreign exchange earner of the country
following coffee, accounting for about eight percent of its total
exports. 
</P>
