<HEADLINE> Ghana Urges Fighting Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ghana on Thursday urged
stakeholders in the African health sector to fight against malaria
 which causes more than one million deaths annually in Africa,
Ghana News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Malaria is more than a health issue and the inaction of other
sectors may increase the burden of the disease," Ghana's minister
of health, Kwaku Danso said in Ghana's capital Accra at a press
briefing on the first African summit on malaria scheduled to be
held in Nigeria on April 25.
</P>
<P>
The summit is co-sponsored by Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo and the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
WHO coordinates the global partnership Roll Back Malaria
Initiative that is aimed at halving the number of malaria deaths
by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 African Heads of State, Group 8 Heads of State,
the heads of 10 international development agencies have been
invited to the Summit.
</P>
<P>
In Ghana, the disease accounts for more than 40 percent of the
Out- Patient Department cases in health institutions.
</P>
<P>
Danso recalled several attempts to control the disease in the
past, including the vector control, but which could not be
sustained due to technical difficulties, lack of funding and
little collaboration with other sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
