<HEADLINE> Mozambique Sets Economic Targets for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The top priorities of the
Mozambican government's economic and social plan for the year 2000
are to eliminate absolute poverty, reduce regional imbalances and
develop the business class, Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi
declared on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the plan to the country's parliament, he said that
the key targets are to achieve a growth rate of between six and
eight percent, and an inflation rate of between eight and ten
percent, to continue establishing conditions for attracting
investments, and to improve the quality of public services.
</P>
<P>
The plan expects an 11.7 percent growth in agriculture, but it
is far from clear how this can now be achieved, given the
devastating floods in five southern and central provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
