<HEADLINE> S. African Farm Attacks Not Related to Zimbabwean Land Invasions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Safety and
Security said on Thursday the recent increase in the number of
farm attacks in South Africa was totally not related to the farm
invasions in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Andre Martins, spokesman for minister Steve Tshwete, said the
government and the national agricultural union, Agriculture SA
(South Africa), were working closely together to address the issue
of farm attacks.
</P>
<P>
"From a law enforcement perspective, if any form of
Zimbabwean-style farm invasions did take place in South Africa,
police would have to act. At the same time we must also remember
that our government has a land restitution process in place,"
Martins said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean war veterans and squatters have been invading
white-owned farms since February, despite the high court order to
evict them from the land.
</P>
<P>
A number of farm attacks have occurred in South Africa in the
last few days, sparking fear that South Africa would undergo the
same situation in Zimbabwe. 
</P>
