<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Prime Minister on successes in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique enjoyed "a positive
performance on all the fronts regarded as fundamental for the
country's social and political life" last year, Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi told the country' s parliament, the Assembly of
the Republic, on thursday.
</P>
<P>
Summarizing achievements in 1999, he said that Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) grew by nine percent, and commodity exports rose by
six percent.
</P>
<P>
Averaged over the year, inflation was only two per cent.
However, in year-on-year terms by the end of December it reached
4.8 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican currency, the metical, devalued by about eight
per cent. This was a considerably higher devaluation than in 1998,
but Mocumbi argued that it was necessary to maintain the
competitiveness of the Mozambican economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that total investment financed with outside resources
(either direct foreign investment, or the contracting of private
foreign loans) reached 742 million U.S. dollars in 1999, as
against only 292 million U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said budgetary policy "achieved its aims,
notably the expansion of public expenditure in a framework of
controlled inflation".
</P>
<P>
Total expenditure increased, in nominal terms, by 23 percent.
Domestic revenue rose by 17 percent, and foreign grants and loans
by nine percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase in spending was channelled mostly to "priority
sectors". Thus there was a 27 percent increase in spending on
education, a 32 percent increase in health, and a 44 percent
increase in the justice system.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi also stressed the debt relief Mozambique received in
1999. At the end of June Mozambique finally reached the
"completion point" for HIPC (Heavily Indebted poor Countries) debt
relief.
</P>
<P>
This wiped out 3.7 billion U.S. dollars of Mozambique's debt
stock in nominal terms (1.7 billion U.S. dollars in present net
value).
</P>
<P>
This improved the balance of payments, and released funds for
poverty reduction programs that would otherwise have been spent on
debt servicing.
</P>
<P>
Annual debt servicing fell from 2.1 percent of GDP in 1998 to
1.7 percent in 1999, Mocumbi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
