<HEADLINE> Zambian President Confirms Ceasefire in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba confirmed on Thursday that fighting in the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC) had ceased after all parties concerned
adopted a disengagement plan two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing at the State House here, he gave an account
of the latest developments regarding the implementation of the
Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement signed last July.
</P>
<P>
The president disclosed that arrangements were already underway
for the establishment of an office in the DRC capital Kinshasa for
former Botswana President Ketumile Masire, who is now official
facilitator of the inter- Congolese political negotiations under
the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Masire had already sent a special envoy to
Kinshasa to arrange for his visit to that country prior to the
holding of crucial inter- Congolese national dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that countries that had sent troops to the DRC
had already begun the release and exchange of prisoners of war and
hostages.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba thanked Senegal and Pakistan for providing battalions
to the 5,500-strong United Nations military observer force and he
called on other countries to emulate them as two more battalions
were needed to raise the required number of observers authorized
by Resolution 1291 of the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
He explained that he had already written to the U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan, under the mandate of SADC, urging him to begin
deployment of U. N. peace-keepers in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The commanders of all parties in the DRC conflict signed an
agreement on disengagement of forces at a meeting of the Joint
Military Commission in Uganda's capital Kampala on April 8.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that after this meeting the commanders of the
armies fighting in the DRC ordered their field commanders to stop
fighting and that these orders had been obeyed.
</P>
<P>
He described the adoption of the plan as a major step forward
in the peace process which effectively removed what was being
cited as an obstacle to the deployment of U.N. observers.
</P>
<P>
The president urged U.N. to begin deployment of the personnel
available now and not necessarily wait until all the troops
authorized by the U.N. resolution are in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
