<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Conference on Trade in Endangered Species Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Li Jinqi Sun Huixia
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Conference of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
ended here on Thursday after adopting a number of decisions on
further protecting dozens of animal and plant species from being
over-exploited.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day meeting, attended by over 2,000 delegates from more
than 100 countries, passed a five-year strategic plan for helping
governments conserve and sustainably use threatened species.
</P>
<P>
The plan also seeks to strengthen national trade enforcement
measures in order to reduce and ultimately eliminate illegal trade
of the endangered species.
</P>
<P>
One of the most closely watched decision made at the meeting
was an agreement to continue the ban on international ivory trade.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the elephant populations in Botswana,
Namibia, South Africa and Zimbabwe will remain on CITES Appendix
II which permits a strictly controlled trade, but the ban on the
ivory trade stays until an effective monitoring system is
established.
</P>
<P>
However, elephant population in other African countries are
still on Appendix I, which bans trade.
</P>
<P>
African elephant range states will continue to seek a
continent-wide consensus on a long-term conservation strategy and
that the ivory ban will be reviewed by the next CITES meeting in
two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
Another decision adopted by the meeting is to maintain the ban
on international trade in whales, which has been in place since
1986. The International Whaling Commission will continue its work
on developing a global management plan for whale stocks.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Cuba's proposal to open up trade in Hawksbill
turtles and their shells failed, as did proposals by Australia,
Britain and the U.S. to regulate trade in the three largest sharks
-- basking, whale and great white sharks.
</P>
<P>
A number of species have been up-listed to CITES Appendix I at
the meeting, including Australian dugong (sea cow), New
Caledonia's horned parakeets, the coelacanth (a fossil fish),
Asia's urial (wild sheep) and Argentina's monkey puzzle tree.
</P>
<P>
Some species, mainly plants, were down listed from Appendix I
to Appendix II or removed completely from the CITES Appendices as
they have recovered sufficiently in number to be no longer
threatened by extinction.
</P>
<P>
In addition to adjusting the Appendices, the delegates made
other decisions on enforcement and national management for highly
endangered species including tigers.
</P>
<P>
CITES, adopted in 1973, is to ensure that no wild animal or
plant species is unsustainably exploited because of international
trade.
</P>
<P>
So far the CITES offers varying degree of protection to more
than 30,000 animal and plant species, depending on their
conditions in the wild and the effect that international trade may
have on their survival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
