<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Prison Population Increased to 1,860,520 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. prisons and jails held 1,
860,520 adults last year, an increase of 60,000 prisoners over the
previous year, according to a Justice Department report.
</P>
<P>
The United States may become the country with the highest rate
of incarceration in the world, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Viewing the latest figures in light of the current U.S.
population, one of every 147 residents was an inmate in an adult
jail or prison at the middle of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that the number of Americans behind bars
will likely surpass 2 million by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
"In the federal system, growth is being driven by drug law
violators and immigration violators coming in," said statistician
Allen J. Beck, author of the report issued here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. prison population has grown steadily for more than a
quarter-century, helped by increased drug prosecutions and tougher
policies against all offenders.
</P>
<P>
Beck said that if the current growth continues, the total
prison and jail population would likely hit 2 million in the
second half of 2001.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.1 million inmates were held in state prisons, about
606,000 men and women in local jails, and about 118,000 in federal
prisons. The prison population was fewer than 800,000 people in
1985.
</P>
<P>
The number of women in U.S. prisons doubled since 1990 to more
than 87,000 in 1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Among black men in their 20s or early 30s, about 11 percent
were in prison or jail, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Louisiana had the highest total incarceration rate, with more
than 1 percent of the state's population imprisoned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Stresses Importance of Comprehensive, Just and Lasting Peace in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 20 (Xinhua)-- The United Nations Security
Council on Thursday adopted a presidential statement, stressing
the importance of, and the need for, achieving a comprehensive,
just and lasting peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council this morning reviewed a letter from U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in which he informed the Council of
Israel's decision to withdraw all its troops from southern Lebanon
by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council endorsed the decision of the Secretary-
General to initiate preparations to enable the United Nations to
carry out its responsibilities under resolutions 425 (1978) and
426(1978).
</P>
<P>
The Council expressed the view that cooperation by all parties
concerned will be required in order to avoid a deterioration of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
The Council welcomed the Secretary-General's decision to send
his Special Envoy to the region as soon as practicable and
encouraged all parties to cooperate fully in the complete
implementation of resolutions 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
The Council looked forward to the Secretary-General reporting
back as soon as possible on relevant development, including the
outcome of the consultations with the parties and all interested
Member States and those contributing troops to the United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon, and his conclusions and recommendations
regarding the plans and requirements for implementation of
resolution 425 and 426 and all other relevant resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Israel on Monday told the Secretary-General that It had
decided to withdraw its troops from Southern Lebanon by July 2000.
Israel promised that it would cooperate fully with the United
Nations in implementing the resolutions of 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
Resolutions 425 and 426 were adopted after Israel's incursion
into southern Lebanon against Palestinian guerrillas in 1978,
which called for immediate cease of Israeli military action
against Lebanese territorial integrity and withdrawal of Israeli
forces from all Lebanon territory.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has since deployed a 4,500 member peacekeeping force
in southern Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
