<HEADLINE> Earnings Rise in UK Stokes Up Rate Hike Worries  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) - The biggest rise in average
earnings in Britain for eight years in February has made an
interest rate rise more likely next month.
</P>
<P>
It is announced the private sector pay increased by an average
6.5 percent in the year to February compared with 4.2 percent in
the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The latest dada, published by the Office For National
Statistics(ONS), showed that as unemployment fell to its lowest
level for 20 years, average earnings rose by 6 percent in the year
to February, the largest increase since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said salaries were partly being boosted by bonus
payments - in particular those earned by people who worked over
the millennium holiday.
</P>
<P>
City economists warned that the Bank of England would almost
certainly use the latest evidence of wage inflation to push up the
cost of borrowing next month.
</P>
<P>
They said that the Bank's monetary policy committee will, after
two months of holding interest rates, raise them again by a
quarter point in May.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also showed that unemployment remained at a 20-
year low in March. The number out of work and claiming benefit
fell 7700 to 1148800, or 4 percent of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the figures, Darshinni David, an economist in
HSBC, said: "If there is any reason the Bank would consider
raising rates again it would be from the labor market."
</P>
<P>
Michael Dicks, at Lehman brothers, said the wage figure was
bound to have a "psychological impact" on the committee. "At 6
percent, that will give quite a different feeling from the 4.5
percent the Bank sees as compatible with its inflation target."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
