<HEADLINE> Quebec Doctor Uses Radioactive Seeds in Cancer Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian doctor is using
radioactive seeds to treat prostate cancer and has achieved
success in more than 80 percent of the cases, the Globe and Mail
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The treatment has prevented relapses in about 144 of a total of
172 cases of prostrate cancer in the past five years after
receiving the "radioactive implants," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jean Pouliot, head of the medical physics research group at
the Centre Hospitalier Universitaire de Quebec, invented the
computer-guided brachytherapy which injects small, intensely
radioactive titanium pellets into a patient's prostate gland to
kill cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
First, Dr. Pouliot uses ultrasound images of a patient's
prostate gland to create a three-dimensional picture to decide
where to place the radioactive seeds, and then he injects between
50 to 100 titanium pellets through ultrasound-guided needles into
the cancerous cells.
</P>
<P>
The new form of brachytherapy can lead to fewer cases of
impotence and urination problems than traditional surgery or
radiation treatments. The patient can go home on the day he
receives the treatment and may return to work within two days,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The patient, however, is made somewhat radioactive at low
levels, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Completes First Evaluation of Third-Generation Telecom System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The China Academy of
Telecommunication Technology (CATT) under the Ministry of
Information and Telecommunication, recently concluded evaluating
the third-generation WCDMA (Wide Code-Division Multiple Access)
system with Ericsson China.
</P>
<P>
"All application and services with the trial WCDMA system have
been tested to meet standards, setting a solid foundation for
China's smooth transition to the new telecom era," said Zhang Ken,
vice president of Ericsson China.
</P>
<P>
The trial system, established in early 1999, has handled voice/
video data, UDI transmissions and high-speed packet data.
</P>
<P>
Zou Tong, deputy director of the science and technology
department of CATT, said, "We have been testing the WCDMA
experimental system provided by Ericsson, and the results are
encouraging us to intensify our cooperation in this area."
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that the achievements of the WCDMA trial system
will help accelerate the commercialization of the third-generation
telecom and the mobile Internet service.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson signed an agreement with CATT in 1998 to install
WCDMA evaluation systems on a trial basis in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
