<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Reformist Councilor Released on Bail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ahmad Hakimipour, member of Tehran
Municipal Council detained last week in alleged connection with an
assassination attempt, was freed on Thursday on bail.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Justice Department said in a statement that Hakimipour
was freed after depositing a bail of 200 million rials (about 24,
000 U.S. dollars at the market rate), the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An open court hearing will be held at Tehran Islamic revolution
court on Tuesday for the suspects involved in an abortive
assassination attempt against Saeed Hajjarian, a close ally of
President Mohammad Khatami, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Hakimipour was arrested last Friday on charges of involvement in
the assassination attempt on the confessions of other people
arrested on the same charge.
</P>
<P>
Hakimipour became a suspect in the assassination because a
letter handed over to Hajjarian, which prepared the ground for the
assassination attempt, was signed by Hakimipour.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, vice chairman of Tehran Municipal Council, was
seriously wounded in a shooting on March 12 in front of the council
hall in downtown Tehran, and was rushed to a nearby hospital by
Hakimipour.
</P>
<P>
The council on Monday lodged a strong protest to Hakimipour's
arrest, saying that "the agents of threat who are known to the
public are free while Hakimipour who had saved the life of
Hajjarian through devotion and self-sacrifice has been arrested."
</P>
<P>
Reformist groups and parties said that bringing Hakimipour's
letter to the assassination scene was a well-designed plot by
certain people to crackdown the reformists, who won an overwhelming
victory in February key parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
But newspapers close to the powerful conservatives, who dominate
most of the country's sensitive organs, urged the authorities to
find the links between Hakimipour and other suspects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
