<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fierce Fighting Rages in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting raged in northern
Sri Lanka Thursday as Tamil Tiger rebels escalated their attacks
on a government camp amid huge losses on both sides, military
officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said a battle was raging around the Iyakachchi military
base on the northernmost Jaffna peninsula with both sides
exchanging heavy artillery and mortar fires.
</P>
<P>
"Heavy fighting is going on now in the northeast of the
Elephant Pass sector," said Military Spokesman Brigadier Palitha
Fernando, adding that the army was now using a new route to keep a
supply line open to the troops in the battle theater.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as the separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) said they had mounted a ferocious offensive against
government forces and captured a section of a key highway in the
peninsula on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE said in a statement sent here from their London office
on Wednesday evening that they took a six-kilometer stretch
between Pallai and Iyakachchi along the strategic A-9 highway
which connects Jaffna with the vital military complex of the
Elephant Pass, a causeway linking the peninsula with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"The LTTE combat formations scored a major military victory ...
when they overran several camps and military bases of Sri Lankan
troops in Massar and Soranpattu area," the LTTE said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had also destroyed several army tanks and blown up
ammunition dumps in the battle theater, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It added following the attacks Sri Lankan soldiers had left
behind "scores of dead soldiers and huge quantities of modern
weapons," but gave no details of their casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense said in a statement on Thursday that
the forward defense line in the Soranpattu and Muhavil areas on
the peninsula had been "readjusted" after heavy fighting.
</P>
<P>
It said 21 troops, including one officer, were killed in action
and 213 were wounded in Wednesday's fighting that erupted after
the LTTE rebels launched a fierce assault on the army the day
before.
</P>
<P>
The statement said more than 35 LTTE rebels were killed and a
large number injured on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest rebel assault began exactly five years after they
pulled out of the peace talks in 1995, breaking a cease-fire by
sinking two naval boats in the eastern port city of Trincomalee.
</P>
<P>
Since then thousands of rebels and soldiers have been killed or
wounded in the fighting, termed by the LTTE Eelam War III, or the
third round of battle in their quest for a separate homeland for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The fresh fighting is an intensified effort by the rebels to
capture the Elephant Pass causeway, the first step to regain their
former stronghold of Jaffna which they lost in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
