<HEADLINE> Commonwealth to Introduce Micro-credit System in Member Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Commonwealth Secretary
General Donald C. McKinnon Thursday said his organization is
planning to introduce micro-credit facilities for employment
generation in the member countries following the Bangladesh model.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opinion exchange meeting with students and
teachers here, McKinnon said the Commonwealth is also planning to
increase stipends and students' exchange programs between member
nations.
</P>
<P>
During meeting with Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina Thursday
afternoon, McKinnon lauded Bangladesh's transition to democracy
and appreciated the program taken by the government in the social
sectors.
</P>
<P>
He particularly lauded the welfare-oriented steps taken by the
government for poverty alleviation and programs in the education
and health sectors.
</P>
<P>
Reciprocating the feeling of the Commonwealth chief, Hasina
said her government would always welcome any cooperation and
assistance from Commonwealth countries for the implementation of
various programs taken for the welfare of the people.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth secretary general also made a courtesy call on
President Shahabuddin Ahmed, who expressed the hope that during
McKinnon's tenure, the horizon of cooperation between Bangladesh
and Commonwealth will further expand. 
</P>
