<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- A federal court on Wednesday gave the Miami relatives of
Elian Gonzalez a potentially significant legal victory when it
ordered that the six-year-old shipwreck survivor must stay in the
United States at least until next month, when it bears their
appeal of a government decision that would return him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Two rigorous studies involving thousands of people have
failed to confirm one of the most widely held beliefs about diet
and health: that eating low-fat, high-fiber foods can reduce the
risk of colon and rectal cancer.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian president-elect Vladimir Putin scored a victory with
regional bosses in parliament's upper chamber, winning a vote to
oust a prosecutor who was the scourge of the Kremlin under former
president Boris Yeltsin. The upper house also gave approval to the
Start II arms reduction pact between Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Stock prices retreated, with the Nasdaq off 87.16 points to
3706.41 and the Dow Jones industrials down 92.46 to 10674.96. The
dollar advanced, but the euro fell to another new low. Meanwhile,
companies' earnings have exceeded Wall Street expectations so far
this reporting season, suggesting the U.S. economy has room to
grow.
</P>
<P>
-- The Italian premier's resignation was accepted, setting off
a scramble to form a new government. Massimo D'Alema, in office
for 18 months, quit after allies lost regional elections on Sunday.
His center-left coalition, bolstered by the Social Democrats'
return, says it has enough votes to retain power. 
</P>
