<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Real Estate Price Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A survey in 35 of China's major
cities showed that real estate prices in China in the first
quarter of this year are stable, compared with the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey released today by the State Development
Planning Commission and the National Bureau of Statistics, the
price of housing went up 0.7 percent, while second-hand housing
and state-owned housing prices rose 1 percent and 2.4 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Land trading price dipped 0.8 percent. However, land trading
prices in some areas increased to vigorous housing sales and land
auctions.
</P>
<P>
Housing leasing prices fell 0.6 percent, but prices for
residential, business, and factory storage housing went up. The
overall fall is mainly due to sluggish leasing for hotels and
restaurants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cleans Up Overseas Tourism Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China will take harsh measures to
crack down on dishonest tourist operators, Peng Zhikai, an
official of the National Tourism Administration (NTA), spoke at
the ongoing China Scenic Spot and Resort Exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Violations are prevalent when some travel services are
organizing overseas trips, he added.
</P>
<P>
Violations include taking tourists to other destinations not on
their itinerary, unqualified travel agencies organizing overseas
trips and misleading advertisements that claim to offer cheap
prices.
</P>
<P>
The NTA revoked the licenses of two travel services in Shenzhen
city and Zhejiang province. They also suspended the right of three
other travel agencies to organize overseas trips during the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The NTA will also increase cooperation with related departments
to improve its overseas tourism market, Peng said.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, approximately two million Chinese toured overseas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Consumer Price Index Down In March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's consumer prices in
overall terms registered a year-on-year rate of decrease of 5.0
percent in March, slightly smaller than in February, according to
the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The decreases were largely attributable to a narrowing of
decline in the prices of clothing and footwear and, to a lesser
extent, also in private housing rentals and the prices of some
consumer durables.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 2000, the price index also declined by
5.1 percent as compared to the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman noted that consumer prices
continued on a down trend in March 2000. The decline was fairly
broad-based across many major commodity groups due to the
prevalence of substantial price discounts at various retail
outlets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yet the decline in consumer prices in overall terms seemed to
have stabilized in the most recent period, along with a firming up
in import prices of some consumer durables, the spokesman added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Epstein's 85th Birthday Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel Epstein blew out candles
marking his 85th birthday today at the Friendship Hotel with more
than 150 Chinese and overseas guests and friends.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jieping and He Luli, vice-chairpersons of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress, and Luo Haocai, vice-
chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, presented a basket of flowers
to Epstein.
</P>
<P>
The Poland-born veteran journalist and writer has devoted 65
years of his life to the Chinese Revolution since he came to China
with his parents in 1917 when he was only 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
He began his journalist career when he was 15 years old. In
1933, he got to know the famous American journalist Edgar Snow and
from that point on, used his pen and plunged into the Chinese
revolutionary cause.
</P>
<P>
He rewrote and finalized the first English news story that
Xinhua News Agency released under the dateline "X.N.R." (China New
Radio) in Summer 1944.
</P>
<P>
He interviewed Mao Zedong in the Yan'an Caves and the Korean
cease-fire agreement signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, he returned to China from the United States, and
joined the magazine "China Reconstructs" at the invitation of
Soong Ching Ling. Later he became executive editor and editor-in-
chief of "China Reconstructs" (now renamed "China Today").
</P>
<P>
Epstein gained Chinese citizenship in 1957 and joined the
Communist Party of China in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese revolution changed his whole life, and he has
always been proud of being a Chinese citizen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
