<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SLA Militiaman Killed, 2 Israeli Soldiers Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 20 (Xinhua) -- One South Lebanon Army (SLA)
militiaman was killed and three others, including a SLA member and
two Israeli soldiers, were injured Thursday morning in south
Lebanon in a series of attacks launched by Lebanese resistance
forces, Oriental Radio station reported.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese resistance forces issued a statement in Beirut saying
that they detonated a big bomb near two Israeli positions of Abala
and Menala in south Lebanon when a Israeli patrol passed.
</P>
<P>
Israeli radio reported that Israel confirmed the casualties
after the attacks.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Hezbollah fired 11 Katyusha rockets at Israeli
positions, but no casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak threatened "cruel retaliatory
blows" if the Katyusha attacks continues. "If the rocket attacks
continue and if people are hit, Israel's response will be cruel.
Once Israel withdraws its troops from south Lebanon to the internal
border there will be no alibi or excuse for anyone to attack
Israel", Barak told state-run Radio Israel Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Israel has notified the United Nations formally that it will
pull out its troops from south Lebanon permanently by July.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied parts of south Lebanon since 1978. It set up
a "security zone" in 1985 saying it needed to protect its northern
settlements from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has since been leading
a war of attrition to try to end the Israeli occupation of south
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
