<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian-Iraqi oil pipeline, stretching from the
Kirkuk oil fields in Iraq to the Banyas port on the Syrian coast,
is expected to open during the next three months.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline is expected to operate at a capacity of 300,000
barrels per day (bpd). And a new pipeline will be constructed with
its capacity estimated at 1.4 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran is currently suffering from an unprecedented wave
of drought which is threatening the country's agriculture and
livestock sectors in many provinces.
</P>
<P>
The drought has hit 15 provinces from a total of 28 provinces,
and rendered losses estimated at 1.37 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Poverty has hit 48 percent of Lebanon's population
while income declining by almost 30 percent against an increase in
spending of 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures are based on a study conducted by the Public Labor
Union in collaboration with the International Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Saudi Arabia have agreed to boost their
cooperation in the fields of exporting motor vehicle spare parts,
producing tire and providing technical and engineering services,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the Wednesday visit to Saudi
Arabia by Director of the Iranian Chamber of Commerce Alinaqi
Khamoushi to follow up agreements reached between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to discuss new fields of economic
cooperation between their chambers of commerce, the agency said.
The manpower available in Iran has attracted the attention of the
Saudi side due to its high capability and dynamism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Revolutionary Guards Deny Coup Intention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Iran's elite Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) on Thursday dismissed the accusation that the
forces would launch a coup d'etat against the reformists, main
supporters of President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a statement, the IRGC said that the body which has taken
shape to safeguard the Islamic republic can never launch a coup
against its own objectives, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC has made separation between the friends and the enemies
of the Islamic revolution and the Iranian nation and the
transparent border has formed the coral part of the IRGC behaviors,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC cited as "enemies" those who attack the aspirations of
the late supreme leader Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini and the religious
sanctities, and politically justify the return of political and
cultural dominance of the world arrogance especially the U.S. and
Israel, and work to break up the national unity.
</P>
<P>
The revolutionary guards complained that certain political
groups have cast doubt over the security environment of the country
and accused the IRGC of making preparation for a coup against the
reformists, the main supporters of President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC said that certain political parties and newspapers have
embarked on propaganda campaign against the body after it issued a
statement on Sunday, which gave a stern warning to the pro-
reformist press that came under mounting pressure of the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The guards, a pillar of the Islamic regime under the direct
control of the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, accused
reformist newspapers of writing articles defending "U.S.-style"
reforms in Iran, which has been already rejected by Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
The power struggle between reformers and conservatives has
intensified since the February parliamentary polling, in which the
newly-grown reformists won an overwhelming victory over the
conservatives, who dominate most of the state organs.
</P>
<P>
The two factions accused each other of having a hand in the
abortive assassination attempt against the life of Saeed Hajjarian,
a reformist leader and a close ally of President Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Over 140 conservative parliamentarians on Wednesday urged the
judiciary to punish Iranian reformists who attended a conference in
Berlin last week on Iran after the February elections and accused
them of advocating the U.S.-style reforms in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reformist parties blast the pro-conservative state
television for screening "selective parts" of the Berlin conference
with an aim to stop the new reformist-dominated parliament from
meeting and undermine Khatami's reform programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
