<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Progress in Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- An additional 415,000 households in
Vietnam rose above the poverty line in 1999, reducing the rate of
hunger and poor households in the country to 13 percent from 15
percent in 1998, Vietnam News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Provinces, cities, ministries and national corporations of the
country last year mobilized nearly 7,000 billion Vietnamese dong (
500 million U.S. dollars) to implement projects on poverty
reduction, according to a report presented at a conference held
here on April 20 and 21.
</P>
<P>
Also in 1999, 508 billion dong (36.28 million dollars) was
spent on infrastructure facility construction and personnel
training for 1,000 communes of special difficulties and border
communes.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than 2,200 communication, irrigation, water
supply, and electricity projects, schools, medical stations and
markets were built in the targeted communes in 37 provinces in
1999.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the United Nations Development Program, the
Asian Development Bank, Canada, Germany, Belgium, the Netherlands,
Sweden and non-governmental organizations of other foreign
countries have granted investments in building medical stations,
schools, irrigation works, and water supply facilities for poor
communes.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam plans to help 300,000 more households out of hunger and
poverty in 2000 with State budget allocations of 1,012 billion
dong (72.28 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Gold, Silver Weak in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Standard gold declined further sharply by 15 rupees (0.35 U.S.
dollar) to close at 4,475 rupees (104.07 dollars) per 10 grams
from the last close of 4,490 rupees (104.42 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two-carat gold was nominally quoted lower at 4,140
rupees (96.28 dollars) per 10 grams as against the previous day's
level of 4,150 rupees (96.51 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ready silver (.999 fineness) showed a fresh fall of
20 rupees (0.46 dollar) at 8,120 rupees (188.84 dollars) per
kilogram from the previous close of 8,140 rupees (189.30 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Raw silver (.916 fineness), however held steady at 8,000 rupees
(186.05 dollars) per kg on some industrial demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
