<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Guatemalan Leader Cancels French Trip, Fearing Detention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Guatemalan president and
current parliament speaker, Efrain Rios Montt, canceled a visit to
France on Wednesday for fears of treading the path of former
Chilean military leader Augusto Pinochet, Le Figaro daily reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was placed under house arrest in 1998 when he was in
Britain for medical treatment after a Spanish lawyer requested his
extradition to Spain for trial on charges of human rights abuses
during Pinochet's rule of iron fist between 1973 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
Montt, who was president of Guatemala between March 1982 and
August 1983, is under investigation by a Spanish judge for his
role in the death of several Spanish citizens in Guatemala during
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry was launched last December after Guatemala's Nobel
Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchu accused the former president
of "crimes of genocide, terrorism and tortures."
</P>
<P>
Montt explained the cancellation of his visit with just one
sentence: "Guatemala is more beautiful."
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro said Montt apparently followed the advice of his
lawyers who reminded him of the "misadventure" of 84-year-old
Pinochet in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, who was detained in Britain on October 16, 1998, was
allowed to return home on March 1, 2000, after British Home
Secretary Jackie Straw ruled that he was physically and mentally
unfit for trial.
</P>
<P>
Montt's parliamentary immunity at home won't help him if he
leaves his country. Pinochet, a senator, also enjoys a life-long
parliamentary immunity from criminal prosecution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falling Car Exports Drag Down Canada's Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Falling car exports dragged down
Canada's trade surplus by half a billion Canadian dollars (about
339 million U.S. dollars) in February, the country's National Post
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Citing the latest figures from Statistics Canada, the paper
said the surplus fell from a record 4.5 billion Canadian dollars
(about 3.1 billion U.S. dollars) in January to 4 billion Canadian
dollars (about 2.7 billion U.S. dollars) in February.
</P>
<P>
The drop highlighted a severe slowdown of auto exports, which
fell 14.1 percent in February from the previous month, as
manufacturers shut plants for inventory purposes.
</P>
<P>
Canadian economists, however, expect the decline to be a
temporary one, saying there is no indication that demand for autos
has waned.
</P>
<P>
"Production difficulties hampered Canada's ability to capture U.
S. demand," Warren Lovely, an economist in Toronto, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The country also saw its imports down 1.2 percent in February
to 28.3 billion Canadian dollars (about 19.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
That decline was led by the machinery, forestry and aircraft
sectors, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
