<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLA Chief of General Staff Holds Talks with Australian Guests (2)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On Sino-U.S. relations, Fu said that Taiwan issue is the most
important and sensitive issue in Sino-U.S. relations. The Chinese
government hopes that the U.S. will earnestly abide by the three
Joint Communiques and other commitments to avoid undermining Sino-
U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese government's principled policy in
resolving the Taiwan issue -- peaceful reunification and one
country, two systems -- has remained unchanged, but it has not
ruled out the possibility of using force.
</P>
<P>
"The PLA has confidence, determination and ability to safeguard
state sovereignty and territorial integrity. Any attempt to split
motherland is doomed to failure," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Fu also mentioned that recently the U.S. and other countries
lodged anti-China resolution at the United Nations Commission on
Human Rights, but failed to pass for the ninth times.
</P>
<P>
It shows that dialogue and cooperation is the general trend,
and favored by the majority of people, and using the human rights
issue as the excuse of confrontation is unpopular and leads
nowhere, he said.
</P>
<P>
Barrie said he is happy to see the frequent exchange of visits
and military cooperation between Australia and China over the past
two years, and expressed his willingness to strengthen the
military cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Barrie reaffirmed that Australia has stuck to "one China"
principle. He noted that China and the U.S. are influential
countries, adding that Australia hopes that Sino-U.S. relations
would maintain a healthy and steady development.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, a ceremony was held to welcome the
Australian guests. Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of General Staff
of the PLA, attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barrie arrived here Wednesday for a 8-day official visit to
China at the invitation of Fu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
