<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Warns against Reformist Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme leader Seyyed Ali
Khamenei issued a severe warning Thursday that some of the
country's newspapers are becoming "enemy strongholds."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a massive gathering of young people at a prayer
ground of the late spiritual leader Imam Khomeini, Khamenei accused
some newspapers for "doing the same thing" as U.S., British and
Israeli agencies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is attempting to hatch plots against Iran through its
radio stations, like what it did in a number of countries including
Eastern European states, Khamenei said, quoted by the official IRNA
news agency.
</P>
<P>
"Some segments of the press" are concentrating efforts on
inciting the public, sowing discord and making the people pessimist
about the social system, he said.
</P>
<P>
The leader called on the press to respect the constitution and
Islamic value, enlighten people, safeguard the country's interests
and write in the interest of the people and Islam.
</P>
<P>
The warning comes when political struggle in the country becomes
heated following February's parliamentary elections, in which
reformers allied to President Mohammad Khatami won an overwhelming
victory, ending the long time conservative majority in the
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei's words echo the effort to take counter-measures
against the reformists by the conservatives, who are still in
control of most of the country's powerful organs and unwilling to
accept the humiliating defeat.
</P>
<P>
One of the steps they took is was limit the activities of
reformist newspapers, which they think are the major tools
reformers use to win support from the people.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives have summoned a number of famous journalists
and publishers to courts on charges of defamation or propagating
against Islamic values, even sending some of them to prison.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing conservative parliament has also passed an
amendment to the press law as part of the effort to curb the
reformist press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
