<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Achieve 65 Percent Literacy by End of 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The rate of literacy in Bangladesh
is expected to reach 65 percent by the end of this year due to
implementation of a range of programs in the education sector,
officials of the Directorate of Non-Formal Education (DNFE) said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government programs as well as those of Non-Government
Organizations (NGOs) have led the rate of literacy to nearly 60
percent by now, and the total success in literacy is expected to
be achieved by the year 2006, they said.
</P>
<P>
During the implementation of the programs to stamp out
illiteracy from the country in the education sector, the DNFE has
been playing a leading role with its four high-profile projects in
more than half of the country's 64 districts.
</P>
<P>
DNFE officials said that as many as 35 million target
population aged 11 to 35 years had been getting non-formal
education through the Total Literacy Movement and the Center-Based
Approach.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-five million young and adult people would be able to
read and write under the Non-Foramal Education Program which will
end next year, they said, adding that Bangladesh is being seen as
a role model by similar countries in the world as the government
together with NGOs is bringing about a tremendous success in the
field of education.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank, the Swiss Agency for Development
and Cooperation, the United States Agency for International
Development, the Norwegian Agency for International Development
and the United Nations Children's Fund are the donor partners of
the government for these projects.
</P>
<P>
DNFE officials said the main objective of the DNFE's national
literacy program is not only to raise the rate of literacy among
youths and adults, but also to reduce gap in literacy between
males and females as well as gap between urban and rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
