<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Reform Tops Nepal Development Forum  by Zhuang Meijie, Song Dejun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The three-day Nepal Development
Forum (NDF) meeting ended in Paris Wednesday with donor countries
committing more financial aid to Nepal while urging the Nepali
government to carry out further reform.
</P>
<P>
The 23 bilateral and multilateral donors participating the
forum reaffirmed their resolve to assist Nepal in addressing the
challenge of poverty alleviation and economic growth, and agreed
to extend a financial assistance of up to 1,250 million U.S.
dollars during 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
However, the donors emphasized that actual levels of assistance
will depend on the progress in policy and institutional reform and
improvements in the effective utilization of the aid, promising
that aid levels could be higher if the pace of reform is
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is one of the poorest countries in the world, with an
annual per capita income of merely 200 U.S. dollars and about 45
percent of its 22 million population living below the poverty line.
About 60 percent of the country's development fund came from
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The donors, however, had complained about the improper use of
the aid money due to poor governance and insisted the aid would be
linked with the performance of the Nepali government.
</P>
<P>
To respond to the donors request for reforms, Nepali Finance
Minister Mahesh Acharya presented an economic reforms package at
the forum.
</P>
<P>
The package encompassed macro-economic restructuring, civil
service reform, anti-corruption initiatives, decentralization,
financial sector and private sector development, aid effectiveness,
and so on.
</P>
<P>
The reform program aims to increase the ratio of public revenue
and gross domestic production, control government expenditure,
keep the GDP and net internal loan ratio under 0.5 percent, bring
auditing of fiscal and industrial sectors at par with
international standard, frame laws about liquidation of industries.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government also pledged to deliver good governance
and reduce corruption by toning up administration, streamlining
ministries, departments and other offices.
</P>
<P>
The donors were impressed by Nepal's commitment for reform, but
"expressed concern for effective implementation of the reform,"
said Hans Rothenbuhler, Country Director of World Bank Nepal
Office, at a video press conference held immediately after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, the Nepali government also appealed for the
donors to ease the stringent conditionalities attached to aid and
change the way they disburse the loans.
</P>
<P>
"We clearly told the donors that the conditionalities tied up
with aid and their aid disbursement practices were cumbersome and
they agreed on the need to reform themselves in this area," said
Acharya at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
Discussion on poverty alleviation strategy was another
important agenda during the meeting. The National Planning
Commission of Nepal presented a Poverty Alleviation Strategy at
the meeting, which was, according to the finance minister,
endorsed by the donors.
</P>
<P>
Apart from development projects, poverty alleviation had
absorbed much of the foreign aid flowing to Nepal. The Nepali
government aims to reduce the poverty level to 10 percent within a
decade, which will prove to be a tough task.
</P>
<P>
The NDF meeting, usually held every two years between Nepal and
its development partners, was held at an interval of four years
this time due to political instability in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The donors had pledged a financial assistance of one billion U.
S. dollars at their last meeting, but only about half of it has
been disbursed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Close to Achieving Zero Poppy Cultivation: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has fulfilled its
international commitment to eradicating production of poppy crop
in the country by bringing it at almost zero level, said a senior
official here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Pakistan's Narcotics Division Muhammad Aziz Khan
told the Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) that there is a minor
spot in Khyber agency of North West Frontier province where the
poppy crop is still being cultivated, adding that the government
is "determined to wash out this menace" soon.
</P>
<P>
NWFP, bordering Afghanistan, once was one of the areas where
poppy was a popular crop.
</P>
<P>
"We have been succeeded to do away with the production of poppy
and confide to achieve zero level poppy cultivation by the end of
year 2000," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Khan said Pakistan's achievement has been appreciated by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
"We have a success story, because Pakistan will no longer be a
drug-producing country," he said.
</P>
<P>
As far as drug addiction is concerned, he said the government
is "fully concerned" over this menace and taking all possible
steps to control it.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, is constantly in touch with the
international agencies to extend all possible cooperation to
effectively deal with this problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
