<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Parliaments Continue Efforts to Fight Against HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Parliaments in the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) region will play an increased
role in helping fight the HIV/AIDS problem, said secretary-general
of SADC's Parliamentary Forum Kasuka Mutukwa on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We must ensure that we don't just let the matter pass by," he
told a media briefing in Cape Town at the end of a six-day forum
conference.
</P>
<P>
The forum will also increase its role in monitoring other
disasters and continue its efforts to promote closer cooperation
among the 13 parliaments within the SADC, Mutukwa said.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Republic of the Congo does not have a parliament
 currently.
</P>
<P>
Other actions agreed by more than 100 senior parliamentarians
at the conference included observing elections in the region and
sharing experiences, building a culture of peace-building,
improving transparency and accountability in governance and
increasing the representation of women in decision-making
structures.
</P>
<P>
According to Mutukwa, SADC heads of state committed themselves
in 1997 to a minimum 30 percent representation by women in all
decision-making structures by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The next SADC Parliamentarian Forum plenary is to take place in
Malawi by the end of October this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
