<HEADLINE> Samaranch Warns Athens Games Against Less Preparation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Athens Games could be showed
the red card unless drastic changes to be made by the 2004 Summer
Olympics organsing committee, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch
said on Wednesday in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
"I told them we are at the end of the yellow phase," Samaranch
told the International Olympic Committee meeting after hearing IOC
officials' reports of a series of major problems and delays in the
preparation for the Athens Games.
</P>
<P>
"If from now until the end of the year there are no drastic
changes, we will enter the red phase."
</P>
<P>
It was an unusally blunt attack from Samaranch, a trained
diplomat, but represented IOC concerns about the structure of the
Greek organisation and problems with subjects like accommodation,
venue construction and transport.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch had told the Greeks that organizing the games
involves three phases: "green" where everything is proceeding
smoothly, "yellow" where there are "many problems," and red where
the "games are in danger."
</P>
<P>
IOC vice president Dick Pound said the IOC could not rule out
moving the games to another country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
