<HEADLINE> One of Every Seven Chinese Newspapers Now On-line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- One out of every seven newspapers
in China is now available on-line.
</P>
<P>
According to information from an international forum on the
Internet here today, 273 newspapers in the country have opened
their own Internet web sites or home pages. Among them, 116
newspapers have their own Internet domain names.
</P>
<P>
Most of the newspapers going on-line are local publications.
Some 56 national newspapers have tested new waters in cyber space,
accounting for one-fourth of the total national newspapers in
China.
</P>
<P>
Most of the sponsors of this international Internet forum are
from Chinese media which have prominent Internet exposure,
including the China Internet Information Center, the People's
Daily, Xinhua, Guangming Daily, Sina, and the Chinese Society of
Information Economy.
</P>
<P>
Today's "Greeting 21st Century -- China Internet Conference"
attracted more than 800 participants from Chinese and overseas
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, China had become one of the eight top
Internet-using countries in the world. Meanwhile, the number of
Chinese web sites has grown from 1,500 to 15,000.  
</P>
