<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Key Laboratories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China will reform its 153 key
laboratories which have contributed greatly to the country's
scientific research and development.
</P>
<P>
Some labs which are behind the times with poor research
equipment and facilities will be cut from the list of state key
labs, and a group of labs which are involved in new and promising
scientific research fields will be selected or built, according to
the Beijing-based newspaper Science Times.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, China has invested 1.4 billion yuan (169 million US
dollars) to build 156 state key laboratories to cover most of the
basic research fields, but only 153 have survived.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1997, the 153 labs had 4,340 permanent
researchers and 14,633 temporary employees, while the total amount
of equipment and facilities was only worth 1.88 billion yuan (
about 226.5 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Shortage of research funding has become a major problem for the
survival and development of these labs. In the future, the central
government will give them more latitude in introducing financing
from outside the research institutes and cooperating with other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The reform will also focus on increasing the innovation work
done in the labs and employing more outstanding young scientists,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
China will unite the labs which are doing similar research work,
and eliminate those which can no longer meet the need of the
scientific development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Reopens Embassy in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
reopened its embassy in the Iraqi capital Baghdad on Thursday,
marking a full recovery of their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, UAE Charge D'affaires in Baghdad Ahmed Abdulla
Bin Saeed said the reopening of the embassy is "a beginning of good
and enhanced relations between the two brotherly countries to serve
their joint interests."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the reopening ceremony, Iraqi Foreign Ministry
Undersecretary Nabiel Najim hailed the UAE move a step forward to
enhance the Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
"The reopening of the embassy is to ensure the life interaction
between the brotherly Arabs in confronting the dangers that the
Arab nations face," he was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is also expected to reopen its consulate in Dubai, the
commercial center of the UAE, in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
The UAE severed its relations with Iraq after the latter invaded
Kuwait in 1990 and took part in the U.S.-led multinational
coalition that drove the Iraqi occupation army out of Kuwait during
the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
However, bilateral relations, especially trade ties, have been
steadily improving in recent years. Trade volume between the two
countries, within the framework of the U.N. oil-for-food program,
has reached 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. humanitarian deal, launched in December 1996,
Iraq is allowed to export a limited amount of crude to finance
imports of food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its
22 million people, who have been badly affected by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan has called for
lifting the trade embargo on Iraq, emphasizing the necessity of
ending the sufferings of the Iraqi people and restoring normal
relations among Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
Three of the six Gulf Cooperation Council member states--
Bahrain, Oman and Qatar--had renewed diplomatic ties with Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
