<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC's Stand on Iraq United: GCC Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) Jameel al-Hujailan said that the GCC
stand on Iraq is united and goes in line with the previous joint
statements issued by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
In an interview which will appear on the Saturday issue of
Kuwait's Arabic weekly magazine Al Zaman (Time), al-Hujailan said
that he did not believe there are conflicting stands among the GCC
members on the Iraqi government, adding that the GCC stand is
clearly specified in its previous statements.
</P>
<P>
The Riyadh-based GCC comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
"Diplomatic relations between some GCC states and Baghdad were
never cut off in the first place, but some states withdrew their
diplomatic representation from Iraq" after Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait in 1990, al-Hujailan said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "if these countries resume their relations with
Iraq today, it would be within their sovereign rights, and if
anyone wants to review the political position of the GCC, then they
have to go back to the group's statements."
</P>
<P>
Al-Hujailan's remarks came after Bahrain announced in early
April that it would reopen its embassy in Baghdad on "humanitarian
grounds" after a 10-year break.
</P>
<P>
Four GCC members--Bahrain, Oman, Qatar and the United Arab
Emirates--have renewed their diplomatic representation in Baghdad.
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia have not re-established ties with Iraq
since the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
