<HEADLINE> Iranian, Lebanese Presidents on Bilateral Ties, Regional Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
and his Lebanese counterpart Emile Lahoud here Thursday exchanged
views on strengthening bilateral ties and promoting regional peace
and stability, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran is willing to cement political, economic, social,
scientific and cultural ties with Lebanon, Khatami told Lahoud, who
arrived here Wednesday afternoon leading a high-ranking delegation.
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed that Iran is interested in regional peace and
stability. But no peace will be durable unless it is based on
justice and restoration of rights of all regional nations, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
On Israel's planned troop withdrawal from south Lebanon by July,
Khatami said that the resistance movement in Lebanon has been the
major cause for such a move.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that all occupied Arab lands will be
liberated and all homeless Palestinians will return to their
homeland peacefully.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Lahoud appreciated Iran's long time support for
Lebanon's resistance against Israeli occupation, stressing that
Iran's backing contributed to the upcoming withdrawal of the
Israeli forces. He also called for further expansion of Tehran-
Beirut relations in all areas.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops have occupied parts of southern Lebanon since
1978. They set up a self-styled security zone there in 1985 with a
claimed aim of protecting its north from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, backed by Iran and Syria, has since
been spearheading a guerrilla war to oust Israeli forces and their
allied South Lebanon Army (SLA) from the country.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet last month endorsed Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's pledge to pull out Israeli soldiers from south Lebanon by
July 7, with or without a peace agreement with Lebanon and its
major power broker Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud also met with Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on
Thursday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the sixth leg of Lahoud's regional tour, which has taken
him to Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar and
Bahrain and will take him to Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
