<HEADLINE> Ghana's Opposition Party Calls for Immediate Address to Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's main opposition New
Patriotic Party (NPP) Wednesday urged the parliament to set up a
bi-partisan committee to assist the Minister of Finance in
stopping the alarming plunge of the national currency, the cedi.
</P>
<P>
The Ghana News Agency Thursday quoted the party's presidential
candidate, John Kufuor as saying that "the committee should
outline proposals that will reduce corruption and capital flight
and propose lasting measures to strengthen our currency and
suggests policies to deal with the economic crisis."
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaian currency had depreciated about 33 percent at the
end of 1999 and 28 percent in the first quarter of 2000 against
the U.S. dollar, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce pressure on the cedi, the government must
"now prepared to live within its means," and take immediate
measures to ensure companies comply with the foreign exchange
retention regulations, said the opposition party leader.
</P>
<P>
He said he disagreed with the government's attempt to blame the
economic problems on the rise in petroleum prices and the decline
in gold price, saying "the fault is not outside this country, it
is inside Ghana." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
