<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa is to Lose 3.6 Billion Dollars This Year on Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Africa lost some two billion U.S.
dollars annually due to Malaria and related diseases in recent
years, the regional director of the World Health Organization
(WTO) said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is expected to reach 3.6 billion dollars this year,
Ebrahim Samba said on Wednesday in Nigerian capital Abuja, which
would host a summit of African states to roll back the scourge
next week, the News Agency of Nigeria reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Samba, in the country for the summit, said in some African
countries Malaria was "responsible for between 30 and 50 percent
of outpatients" and 15 percent of hospital admissions.
</P>
<P>
He said the objective of the summit, which has the support of
the Geneva based organization, was a "progressive reduction of
deaths due to malaria by 50 percent by 2010, another 30 percent
and 20 percent respectively by 2015 and 2025.
</P>
<P>
A key feature of the program is its multi-faceted approach,
including the mobilization of a global coalition that would
include the leaders of endemic countries, United Nations
agencies, non-governmental agencies and the scientific community.
</P>
<P>
The director said some 50 African leaders, leaders of eight
leading industrial countries and 10 international development
agencies have been invited to the Abuja summit, expected to be
opened by Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo on April 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
