<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Organization of Asia-Pacific News Agencies Holds Session in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The 11th General Assembly of the
Organization of Asia-Pacific News Agencies (OANA) opened Thursday
at the President Hotel in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
During its four-day work, the assembly will discuss prospects
for the organization's operations, practical issues of its
activity, including creation and technological support for an OANA
site on Internet for round-the-clock exchange of information among
its participants in real time.
</P>
<P>
The assembly participants will also elect new OANA president,
vice-presidents and Secretary-General, fix a place and date for
the next OANA General Assembly in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The forum is attended by over 100 representatives from the
United Nations and news agencies of nearly 40 countries, including
the Xinhua News Agency, the Itar-Tass news agency, the association
of independent CIS (the Commonwealth of Independent States) news
agencies, the federation of Arab agencies, and other regional news
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin sent a congratulation
letter Thursday to the forum, calling the joint work of OANA
members "an example of fruitful cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Delegates and guests will meet prominent Russian politicians,
businessmen and mass media leaders at a special session of the
General Assembly on Friday.
</P>
<P>
OANA, established in 1961 at the initiative of the United
Nations and UNESCO, groups news and information agencies from 34
countries, including China, Russia, India, Indonesia, Japan,
Vietnam, Malaysia and other states in the Asia-Pacific region,
where more than one-half of the world population lives.
</P>
<P>
The OANA members are now responsible for two-thirds of
information circulated in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
