<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Publisher Withdraws Camus' "Journal" for Suspected Anti- Semitism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The French publishing house
Editions Fayard on Thursday withdrew a diary book for containing
suspected anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
Fayard has asked all bookstores to withdraw copies of "Journal"
by Renaud Camus, because the book risks to provoke a dispute, said
the general director of the publishing house, Olivier Betourne.
</P>
<P>
Two leading media figures of France Wednesday condemned the
book for criticizing the large presence of Jews in a radio and
television program, France Culture.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Marie Cavada, the president of Radio France, and Laure
Adler, director of France Culture, expressed their indignation at
the book and threatened to launch lawsuit against its writer and
publisher.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Culture and Communication, Catherine Tasca, has
also expressed her discontent about the book.
</P>
<P>
Camus said in the book that the Jews in the "Panorama" program
of France Culture are "over-represented as an ethnic and religious
group."
</P>
<P>
He also criticized France Culture for making at least one
program each week on "Jewish culture, Jewish religion, Jewish
writers, the state of Israel and its policy, the life of Jews in
France and in the world today or through the centuries."
</P>
<P>
France strictly bans books with anti-Semitic connotation.
</P>
<P>
Writer Roger Garaudy was condemned two years ago for publishing
a book in which he expressed doubt over the official number of
Jews who were killed in the Holocaust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
