<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pudong Emphasizes Ecological Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the Lujiazui Financial and Trade Zone, known as China's "
Wall Street," is a collection of gleaming high-rise financial
buildings. Every inch of land there is expensive, but city
planners, after consulting international designers, went ahead
with construction of the park's 140 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The Central Park, with an expanse of lawn, artificial hills,
and pavilions, has become a tourist attraction, receiving 700,000
visitors so far.
</P>
<P>
The park, which connects with the 5.5-kilometer Boulevard
Century, has boosted property sales in surrounding areas. One
residential quarter, Tianan Huayuan, is among the beneficiaries as
its housing prices there have jumped from 4,500 yuan to 6,300 yuan
per square meter.
</P>
<P>
Another famed ecological project is in Zhangjiabang, where the
government tackled pollution in a river with 250 million yuan (
about 30 US dollars). The river has helped increase tourism
earnings as well as real estate profits.
</P>
<P>
At present, Pudong's annual tourism earnings stand at 1.1
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, green space per capita has
risen to 7.77 square meters from 0.54 square meters, while
pollution in 90 percent of Pudong has been controlled.
</P>
<P>
China began developing the 522-square-kilometer area on the
eastern side of Huangpu River on April 18, 1990, in a drive to
reinvigorate Shanghai as an international trade and financial
center.
</P>
<P>
Pudong New Area Administrative Committee officials said they
have realized that a sound ecological environment is also
necessary for attracting foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
