<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Boast Spacecraft Welding Techniques </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China has successfully applied
advanced welding techniques to the building of its first
outerspace aircraft, named "shenzhou", which was launched last
November, according to a recent appraisal by a committee made up
of members of Chinese Academy of Sciences and Academy of
Engineering of China.
</P>
<P>
The techniques, combination welding and deformation control,
were applied to the return cabin of the experimental spacecraft,
which touched down without any damage, fully indicating that China
's spacecraft welding technique is mature and has reached the
world advanced level.
</P>
<P>
Joint efforts have been made by the National Key Lab of Modern
Welding Technology at Harbin Polytechnical University and the
Chinese Research Institute of Space Technology (CRIST) for the
techniques.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chunqing, deputy director with the lab, said that the
shell of the spacecraft's return cabin, which is no more than two-
millimeter thick, is usually made of aluminum alloy. Any
deformation during the welding process might lead to breach caused
by heat when the return cabin falls down.
</P>
<P>
With the help of precise clamping apparatus developed by China
and other new techniques, experts successfully solved the welding
problems on a 70-meter-long welding line on the cabin shell, which
stood the test of the return.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that his lab and CRIST are cooperating in the
development of a technique of automatic welding of space curve and
a technique of forecast of welding deformation on thin shells.
</P>
<P>
He said the two techniques will enhance China's level on the
shell-welding of spacecrafts and set a solid ground for the future
launch of manned spacecraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Historians Focus on Borderland Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese historians are looking to
the past to find solutions to modern-day problems in the border
areas.
</P>
<P>
A new study on borderlands will take an in-depth look at
historic events in those areas, said Ma Dazheng, director of the
Research Center for Chinese Borderland History and Geography under
the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS).
</P>
<P>
The research center formulated a 12-year plan extending from
1990 to 2001, listing Xinjiang Uygur and Tibet autonomous regions,
northeast China, Yunnan Province and the Nansha Islands as four
key study points, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the center organized experts to compile five sets of
academic books and journals. A seven-volume General History of
Chinese Borderland, with more than six million Chinese characters,
will be published in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
The center, established in 1983, remains the only research body
on borderland history in the People's Republic.
</P>
<P>
Descriptions on borderland history and geography in ancient
times can be found in inscriptions on bones and tortoise shells of
the Shang Dynasty (16th-11th century B.C.).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
