<HEADLINE> Malaysia Approves 35 Bln U.S. Dlr DFI Last Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia approved 133.09
billion ringgit (35 billion U.S. dollars) of direct foreign
investment(DFI) in manufacturing projects in the decade from 1990
to 1999, Deputy International Trade and Industry Minister Kerk
Choo Ting said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia got the biggest chunk of foreign capital inflow among
countries in the region, he told the Senate here during question
time.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the largest investor accounting for 27.
3592 billion ringgit (7.199 billion U.S. dollars) or 20.6 percent
of total foreign investment, followed by Japan with 25.7676
billion ringgit(6.78 billion U.S. dollars), Chinese Taipei with 20.
0455 billion ringgit (5.275 billion U.S. dollars), Singapore with
12.9635 billion ringgit (3.411 billion U.S. dollars) and South
Korea with 5.1262 billion ringgit (1.349 billion U.S. dollars), he
said.
</P>
<P>
The top five foreign investors account for 68.6 percent of
total foreign investment. 
</P>
