<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Expects 20m Ton Wheat Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If the target is met, there will be no need of importing wheat
thus saving 700 million rupees (13.4 million U.S.dollars) of
foreign exchange, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to details, the country needs an estimated 19 million
tons of wheat for its domestic requirements.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, 18 million ton wheat was produced in the South Asian
country whereas 1.6 million wheat was imported to meet the
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
The current government has offered more incentives to farmers
aimed at increasing wheat production and achieving self-reliance
in agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the procuring price of the crop was the most
significant motivation for the farmers to grow more wheat than the
previous year. The government has enhanced wheat price from 240
rupees (4.6 dollars) per kilogram to 300 rupees (5.8 dollars) per
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
In Punjab, the main wheat-growing province, the crop was
cultivated this year at 1.544 million acres of land, 5.1 percent
higher than the last year. Wheat production in Punjab is expected
about 14.5 million tons which is 300,000 tons more than the target
set at the beginning of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
