<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Swimmers Close to World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Masami Tanaka and Mai Nakamura set
their national records for a second straight day at the Japanese
swimming championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tanaka, who set her own national record of 1:07.38 in the women
's 100-meter breaststroke on Wednesday, bettered it again by
clocking 1:07.27 to win today's final.
</P>
<P>
Nakamura, who also set a new mark of 1:00.89 on Wednesday in
the women's 100m backstroke, improved it by 11 hundredths of a
second to win her final.
</P>
<P>
Tanaka's time was faster than the winning time of 1:08.42 set
by American Kristy Kowal at the 1998 World Championships in Perth,
and that of 1:07.73 set by Penny Heyns of South Africa at the
Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Nakamura was also faster than American Lea Maurer's world
winning time of 1:01.16 and American Beth Botsford's Olympic
winning time of 1:01.19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
