<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Separatist Remarks Illogical, Illegal: Taiwan Issue Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- No matter who is elected leader
of Taiwan, Taiwan is undeniably a part of China, Professor Huang
Jiashu of the People's University said today.
</P>
<P>
Annette Lu's remarks on "Taiwan independence" ignored this
basic fact, and are illogical and illegal, he told Xinhua in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
The professor pointed out that Annette Lu's claim that the
cross-straits relationship is one of "distant relatives and close
neighbors" is absurd.
</P>
<P>
"Lu just wants to let the world know that at the moment the
Kuomintang stepped down from power, Taiwan and the mainland no
longer had any relations, and so Taiwan can have independence,"
said Huang, adding that Lu's sole intention is to separate Taiwan
from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Huang stressed that the struggle of any political party is an
internal affair of a country and should not affect the nation's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The People's Republic of China, since it was founded in 1949,
has replaced the Republic of China to become the sole legitimate
representative of China, and exercise full sovereignty over China,
including that over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
It is a common thing that parties rule in turn in Western
countries, but this has nothing to do with a country's sovereignty,
not to speak of the recent election in Taiwan that only concerns a
change in the regional leader, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's one-China stance has been acknowledged
and supported by the international community. Annette Lu's aim to
separate China's sovereignty and territory, using the party shift
as a cover, is doomed to fail, said Huang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
