<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military to Speed Up Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Military (TNI)
pledges that it will speed-up its internal reforms process in line
with the on-going national reforms agenda and will leave soon its
political role, a senior military officer said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The TNI will continue its internal reforms process and fasten
such a process," TNI Chief Adm. Widodo A.S. told a press
conference after presiding over a two-days TNI leadership meeting
at its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"We also committed to leave our political role. The TNI will
not involve again in political constellation and will then focus
on its tasks in defence sectors," the Admiral added.
</P>
<P>
Widodo said that the TNI's internal reforms was among issues
which has been seriously discussed during the two-days leadership
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The TNI has experienced significant changes," Widodo said.
</P>
<P>
The TNI has been under fire as its alleged involvement in
atrocities policy in the breakaway province of East Timor since
the territory overwhelmingly voted in favor of independence in a U.
N.-sponsored direct ballot in August 1999.
</P>
<P>
Widodo also reiterated the TNI's commitment to continue its
participation in international tasks to secure the world peace in
line with the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
"During the meeting, we also committed to strengthen our stance
in holding up the supremacy of law. It is clear that the TNI backs
the supremacy of law," Widodo added.
</P>
<P>
But Widodo also admitted that in its bid to develop its
abilities as well as enhancing its defence system, the TNI faces
problems due to lack of fund.
</P>
<P>
The government previously proposed a defense budget of 10.1
trillion rupiah (1.442 billion U.S. dollars) for the current April-
December fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
But the House of Representatives then only approved 8.235
trillion rupiah (1.176 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Therefore in this context, we (TNI) will not make a
significant additional force," he said.
</P>
<P>
The number of the TNI personnel now is about 250,000 personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
