<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Trade Continues to Expand in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's external trade
continued to expand in March 2000 with the total volume growing by
23.8 percent to hit 38.60 billion Singapore dollars (about 22.73
billion U.S. dollars), according to a monthly bulletin released
Thursday by Singapore Trade Development Board.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the same month last year, non-oil domestic exports
(NODX) rose by 14.5 percent to reach 9.76 billion Singapore
dollars (about 5.75 billion U.S. dollars), non-oil re-export
increased by a strong 28 percent to 8.42 billion Singapore dollars
(about 4.95 billion U.S. dollars), non-oil imports registered a
growth of 20 percent with a volume of 16.99 billion Singapore
dollars (about 10.01 billion U.S. dollars) and oil domestic
exports expanded by 53.4 percent as a result of the surge in oil
price.
</P>
<P>
During the month, domestic exports of electronics increased by
9.8 percent spurned by strong exports of integrated circuits and
telecommunication equipment, and that of the non-electronic
products rose by 24.2 percent which was largely contributed by the
strong demand for electrical circuit apparatus and petrochemicals
to the region, as well as disc media products (packaged software)
to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports to the United States, Malaysia, Japan
and Hong Kong registered positive growth in March 2000 while that
to the EU market continued to decline by 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the top NODX exports markets, NODX to Hong Kong recorded an
upsurge of 44.9 percent while figures to Malaysia, Japan and the U.
S. picked up by 29 percent, 33.6 percent and 4.5 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
NODX to the emerging markets saw a 23 percent expansion in
March 2000 which was bolstered by strong demand from India and
Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
