<HEADLINE> SADC Trade Protocol Ready for Signing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited signing of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) trade protocol is
expected to take place in September this year following a
successful meeting in South Africa recently.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia newspaper Thursday quoted Norman Chibamba,
Zambian Commerce, Trade and Industry Deputy Minister, as saying in
an interview in Lusaka on Wednesday that the negotiations were
almost concluded.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the protocol would be done during the heads of
state summit scheduled for September in Namibia, Chibamba said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that before the summit there would be one more
ministerial meeting to work on final touches. Most differences
which caused the delay have been ironed out, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Zambian government was aware of the anxiety of the
business community to see the signing which would allow them to
penetrate regional markets.
</P>
<P>
Once the agreement comes into effect, it would create a great
relief to many business houses in Zambia which have been looking
forward to the SADC protocol, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SACD protocol, Chibamba said, would foster economic
cooperation among member states and remove obstacles to the free
movement of services and capital within SADC, he said. 
</P>
