<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Conflict Resolution in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has called on the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) and the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) to resolve regional conflicts in the Great
Lakes region and in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Thursday quoted Glyne Michelo,
Export Board of Zambia (EBZ) marketing officer, as saying that
these are Zambia's main potential markets, without which a Free
Trade Area (FTA) will not make much sense.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes states and Angola are some of Zambia's major
markets for cement, wheat flour, footwear, lime, coal and sugar,
with potential even for food items, Michelo said at the just ended
Cross Border Initiative workshop held in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
He said that internal and regional civil strife has been the
impeding factor to full exploitation of this potential.
</P>
<P>
The official called for quick resolution of the issues for
COMESA FTA to have immediate benefits for Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to EBZ, a senior official of the COMESA Secretariat
said in an interview that progress has already been made in the
co-ordination between COMESA and other Treaties to cooperate in
the promotion of peace, security and stability.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be named, stated that at a
meeting last month, the regional leaders noted that the prevalence
of conflicts in the region is a hindrance to the regional economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
They agreed on the need for all the member states to strive for
peace, security and stability in the region as provided under
article 163 of the COMESA treaty, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that member states will continue to meet to seek
peaceful solutions to these conflicts within the framework of the
OAU and in accordance with the United Nations Security Council
resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
