<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Supports Moscow's Ratification of START-II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Wednesday expressed support for
Russia's ratification of the 1993 Russian-U.S. Strategic Arms
Reduction Treaty-2 (START-II).
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry spokesman told the press Thursday that the
DPRK fully supports all efforts for the achievement of disarmament
and world peace.
</P>
<P>
On April 14, Russia's State Duma, lower house of parliament,
ratified the treaty, under which, the U.S. and Russia each would
cut their nuclear warheads from 6,000 to no more than 3,500 by
2007. The U.S. Senate approved the treaty in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman criticized the United States' move to create a
national missile defense system and intention to withdraw from the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) Treaty, asking Washington to
completely withdraw and destroy nuclear weapons deployed in South
Korea and "not to initiate a new arms race." 
</P>
</TEXT>
