<HEADLINE> Russian GDP Grows 8 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia's gross domestic product (
GDP) grew about 8 percent in the first quarter of this year,
Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin announced at a cabinet
meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In March, the growth was a little slower but surpassed 6
percent, and "for the first time in modern history, inflation
amounted to 0.6 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not just steady, but also enormous growth," Putin said.
"It gives reasons to some experts to believe that the Russian
economy may be called robust," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Today we have better indicators than those predicted for 2001,
" Putin said, quoting forecasts as saying that in 2001 the GDP
will increase by 4-4.5 percent to 6-6.9 trillion rubles (209.89-
241.3 billion U.S. dollars) and inflation will fall to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to raise salaries and pensions not at the same
rates, but at higher ones," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Putin stressed the importance of the debate on economic
development scenarios for next year and until 2003 under the
present circumstances. "After the presidential elections and ahead
of the coming formation of the government, significant interest
will be shown in this," he said.
</P>
<P>
"During today's discussion we should proceed from the
understanding that it is tentative and changes may be made related
to the development of Russia's long-term economic strategy," Putin
told his ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
