<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Airlines Report Mixed Financial Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Major U.S. airlines Wednesday
reported mixed financial results for the first quarter, with some
operators overcoming higher fuel prices and beating estimates,
while labor troubles and other factors hurting others, according
to reports from various airlines.
</P>
<P>
"The common thread is very strong revenues toward the end of
March," Brian Harris, airline analyst at Salomon Smith Barney,
said.
</P>
<P>
Among the airlines beating analysts' estimates were UAL Corp.,
parent of the United Airlines; the world's largest airline, AMR.
Corp., parent of No. 2 U.S. carrier American Airlines; No. 8 Trans
World Airlines Inc. and No. 9 America West Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
No. 6 US Airways Group Inc., which narrowly averted a shutdown
by reaching a contract agreement with its flight attendants and No.
10 Alaska Air Group Inc. came in below estimates.
</P>
<P>
"We simply could not overcome the drastic increase in fuel
prices," John Kelly, Alaska Air chairman and chief executive, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Fuel prices had surged earlier in the quarter to their highest
levels since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The owner of the United Airlines, the nation's largest carrier,
reported an unexpected gain in first-quarter income and raised its
earnings guidance for the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
United's parent UAL Corp. earned 191 million U.S. dollars, or 1.
61 dollars a share, excluding two one-time charges. Analysts
surveyed by earnings tracker First Call had expected earnings to
fall to 1.37 dollars a share in the period from the 187 million
dollars, or 1.54 dollars a diluted share, which it earned from
operations in the year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
Revenue rose nine percent to 4.5 billion dollars from 4.2
billion dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Fuel costs increased 36.5 percent to 539 million dollars, but
that was less severe than at many other carriers because they were
mitigated by greater use of long-term fuel contracts than some
competitors.
</P>
<P>
The company made up for the fuel hikes by cutting commissions
paid by 12 percent to 249 million dollars, and reducing employee
stock ownership plan compensation expense in half to 91 million
dollars. The airlines have all cut the fees paid to travel agents.
</P>
<P>
AMR Corp., the parent of American Airlines, posted a profit of
89 million dollars, or 57 cents and share, from a loss of two
million dollars, or one cent a share, in the year earlier period.
Analysts polled by First Call forecast it would make 39 cents a
share in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
The world's second largest airline was hit by a pilots walkout
in the first-quarter last year, but AMR posted a profit this
quarter despite a 60-percent surge in fuel cost to 553 million
dollars. Revenue rose 14.2 percent to 4.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Although fuel costs were up sharply from last year, the
increase was dampened to a large degree by our ongoing fuel
hedging program," said Donald Carty, AMR's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
Trans World Airlines reported a loss of 63.9 million dollars,
or 98 cents a share, before an accounting change. While that was
wider than the 62 cents a share loss it reported a year earlier,
it was below the First Call forecast of 1.37 dollars a share loss.
</P>
<P>
Including the charge for a change in accounting practices in
the most recent quarter and a gain from sale of investment in the
year-earlier quarter, the company reported a net loss of 76.1
million dollars, or 1.16 dollars a share, up from 21.6 million
dollars, or 42 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
The St. Louis-based carrier's revenue rose 5.8 percent to 809.0
million dollars from 764.6 million dollars, due in part to higher
fares. Most major airlines instituted fuel surcharges during the
quarter to deal with the fuel piece hikes.
</P>
<P>
Fuel costs nearly doubled for TWA to 140.4 million dollars from
72.6 million dollars a year ago. Labor costs climbed eight percent
to 25.3 million dollars under a new labor agreement. But
commissions fell by 30 percent, saving 13.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
US Airways went to the brink of a shut-down last month before
reaching a contract agreement with its flight attendants. But
preparations for that possible shut-down and the loss of traffic
to other carriers cost the troubled airline, which also was hit
with some of the steepest fuel increases in the industry.
</P>
<P>
The Arlington-Va.-based carrier reported a loss of 108 million
dollars, or 1.72 dollars a diluted share, well above the First
Call forecast of 1.48 dollars a share. A year earlier, the company
posted net income of 46 million dollars, or 56 cents a diluted
share, but seven cents of that came from the sale of its share of
the industry-wide Equant communications network.
</P>
<P>
With the change in accounting practices, US Airways' net loss
came to 211 million dollars, or 3.27 dollars a diluted share.
</P>
<P>
US Airways' average fuel price rose 105 percent to 88.8 cents a
gallon from 43.3 cents a year earlier. That hike, and increased
flights, drove total fuel expenses up 113 percent to 253 million
dollars. While commissions fell 26.5 percent, that saved the
carrier only 30 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Revenue was basically flat for the period, rising 0.9 percent
to 2.1 billion dollars from 2.0 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
US Airways said that with fuel prices starting to decrease and
labor disputes finally settled, the rest of the year should show
improvement.
</P>
<P>
"The unique challenges US Airways faced over the past year are
largely behind us," President and CEO Rakesh Gangwal said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
