<HEADLINE> China to Set up Photoelectron Valley in Northeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Plans are underway to establish
a "Photoelectron Valley of China" in the city of Changchun in
northeast China's Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, under the auspices of the Changchun Institute of
Optics and Fine Mechanics and Physics under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, and the Changchun Economic Development Zone, will be
crucial for the development of the country's photoelectron
industry and national defense, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
Photoelectrons are expected to be one of the pillar industries
in the 21st century, and the Changchun Photoelectronic Industrial
Park, covering an area of 2.12 million sq.m., will become a
development center, production and trade base, and an information
exchange center for photoelectron products and research.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the involvement of foreign investment in the
project, so we can become more competitive both at home and in the
global market," said Cao Jianlin, the institute director.
</P>
<P>
The institute has been known as the cradle of photoelectrons
since the founding of New China in 1949, and it has developed into
the most authoritative base in the country for optic materials,
fine mechanics, and practical optics. 
</P>
