<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Boost Handicraft Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam plans to increase its
handicraft export turnover from the 1999 figure of 170 million U.S
dollars to 250 million U.S. dollars in 2000, Vietnam News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fine art and handicraft products are among Vietnam's top hard
currency earners, with outlets covering 50 countries and
territories in the world.
</P>
<P>
Each year, Vietnam exports to Japan large quantities of wood
furniture and ceramics, valued at 60 million U.S. dollars and 5
million U.S. dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam earned 66 million U.S. dollars from exports of fine
arts and handicraft articles in the first quarter of this year, a
year-on-year increase of 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has, with its abundant labour force and access to
materials, great potential to develop handicraft production in
flourishing traditional craft villages like Bat Trang (ceramics),
Dong Ky (wood furniture) and Dai Bai (bronze articles).
</P>
<P>
Vietnam hopes to increase handicraft exports from 250 million U.
S.dollars this year to 1 billion U.S. dollars by 2005.
</P>
<P>
To meet increasing demand for handicrafts, the country has
given priorities to develop the handicraft sector and the Ministry
of Trade has completed a handicraft development project which will
submitted to the Government for approval at the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
