<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White Farmers, War Veterans Declare Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Zimbabwe's war veterans
and white farmers met here on Wednesday and pledged to work out a
plan that would result in an amicable solution to the current land
issue, the daily Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the former fighters would not withdraw from the farms they
occupied in the meantime, the report said.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe, who hosted the meeting with
representatives of the war veterans and the farmers, told a press
conference that farmers who had withdrawn from their properties
should now go back as the two sides had agreed not to engage in
violence.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to meet again next week to find a
lasting solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Zimbabwe National Liberation War Veterans'
Association Chenjerai Hunzvi, President of the Commercial Farmers'
Union Tim Henwood and President of the Zimbabwe Tobacco
Association Richard Tate attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The former freedom fighters have occupied about 1,000
white-owned farms since February this year.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe briefed the war veterans on the farmers' concerns about
"what they regarded as the absence of security" on the farms.
</P>
<P>
"The war veterans expressed to me what their own concerns were
and so when we met the two sides, they were able to express to
each other what their concerns were," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, "the farmers are talking about the
need for security for them to be able to carry out their normal
duties -- especially taking into account the current season."
</P>
<P>
The war veterans expressed concern that after so many years
they had realized that there was resistance by farmers to
redistribute land for resettlement, resulting in the current land
occupations.
</P>
<P>
"They then tried to see what solution could be found in the
meantime. I was happy that this meeting was held. I was also
happy that it created an understanding," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that police or the army would not be
deployed to the farms as both the farmers and the war veterans had
made a commitment against violence.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the war veterans said that the farmers
should demonstrate their commitment to the land reforms by
stopping their court case against the farm occupations, alleged
military training of farm workers and stockpiling of arms on the
farms.
</P>
<P>
Henwood said he believed a solution would be reached and the
two parties would meet again soon for further discussions aimed at
reaching an amicable solution.
</P>
<P>
On his side, Hunzvi said that "I am very happy that we managed
to meet at last. We have to work to see that we find a solution.
We have agreed that hostilities should cease and that we should
work toward a solution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
