<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Congratulates Rwandan President-elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has congratulated Paul Kagame on his being elected president of
Rwanda and reiterated his commitment to extend good cooperation
with the latter.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Press Secretary Hope Kivengere confirmed this in a
 telephone interview with Xinhua Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has sent a message of
congratulation to Paul Kagame in which our president wishes him
well," Hope said.
</P>
<P>
However, she said the president has still not yet told her
whether he would attend the April 22 swearing-in ceremony of
Kagame.
</P>
<P>
"He would sent a delegation there if he himself cannot attend,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The Monitor newspaper Thursday quoted media reports in Kigali
as saying that President Museveni promised to work closely with
the Rwandan president- elect toward the restoration of peace in
the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Kagame is the first Tutsi president of Rwanda since the small
central African country won its independence in 1962.
</P>
<P>
The 43-year-old president-elect, who had spent over 30 years in
Uganda and served as Rwandan vice president and minister of
defense before the presidential election sparked by resignation of
former President Pasteur Bizimungu in March, had special
relationship with Museveni.
</P>
<P>
Museveni and Kagame, close allies in the conflict of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), have experienced strained
relations due to armed clashes of their troops in Kisangani in
northeastern DRC in August, 1999.
</P>
<P>
They have made strenuous efforts toward relation normalization
since the Kisangani incident. However, it is widely believed that
it will take time to mend the fences.
</P>
<P>
Kagame was elected President of Rwanda on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
