<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8,000 Tanzanian Expectant Mothers Die Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- About 8,000 Tanzanian women
die each year from causes related to pregnancy and child delivery,
the African newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At least 20 expecting mothers die every day and findings about
maternal mortality rates indicate that the problem occurs to a
large number of families, according to Ali Nzige, director of
Preventive Services in the Tanzanian Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Death rates among expectant mothers in Tanzania is at least 100
 times higher than those in Europe and North America, the director
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the alarming figure is a sad reminder that all must be
done to enable pregnant women to receive attention without undue
frustration in maternal clinics.
</P>
<P>
Many such deaths are preventable as they arose from erroneous
advice at household level, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that frequency of childbirth, poor services in district
and regional hospitals are often to blame, as nurses take time to
recognize an emergency and often do not have sufficient skills to
handle such cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
