<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Loan-Sharking Ring Busted in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A loan-sharking ring from Hong
Kong was busted by police in Hong Kong and the city of Shenzhen in
south China's Guangdong Province bordering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The ring had its headquarters in Shenzhen, and made loans to
people and businesses in Hong Kong at usury rates, operating under
the cover of a financial service company.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen police cooperated closely with their counterparts in
Hong Kong during the investigation, and seized large amounts of
criminal evidence against the ring, including a computer program
of the usury scheme and a database detailing the dealings and
debtors' bank cards.
</P>
<P>
The two police departments jointly launched an operation to
seize the ring's control center in Shenzhen on April 17, leading
to the arrest of 10 suspects including the ring lead, who is known
as Wen.
</P>
<P>
According to the police's investigation, the ring members used
force and the threat of violence to intimidate debtors in Hong
Kong, thus posing a threat to social security.
</P>
<P>
Police in Shenzhen and Hong Kong have arrested a total of 30
ring members. Police in Guangdong have vowed to further strengthen
cooperation with their Hong Kong counterparts in cracking down on
criminals in the two regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
