<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 700 Rare Books Returned to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Some 700 rare books have been
returned to China after an absence of nearly one hundred years.
</P>
<P>
Well-known Chinese-American octogenarian collector Weng Wan'ge
recently agreed to transfer these books, some of which are the
only existing copies in the world, to an organization in Shanghai,
the Wenhui Daily reported yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese antique dealers regard this group of books as "very
precious," with extremely high artistic and academic value, the
Shanghai-based newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
These books were part of the large collection held by Weng, a
direct descendant of Weng Tonghe who was the mentor of Emperor
Guangxu (1875-1908) of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
In early 1900's, Weng's family secretly transported most of
their possessions overseas during a period of constant war in
China, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, Chinese relics experts said they believed that the
rare books were lost during wartime.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, some of these rare books appeared at an
exhibition organized by the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
After strenuous persuasion by experts from China Guardian
Auction Co., Ltd., Weng agreed to sell the rare books in one batch
to a high-level Chinese museum or library via the auction firm,
the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Chinese Medicine Education Stresses Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Seasoned traditional Chinese
medicine experts are finding more people following in their
footsteps to become qualified doctors, today's People's Daily
reports.
</P>
<P>
Traditional Chinese medicine stresses the accumulation of
knowledge and personal accomplishment, and its educational method
is "one to one," which means one teacher can only teach only one
student at a time.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine spends
500,000 yuan every year to promote traditional Chinese medicine
education.
</P>
<P>
About 627 traditional Chinese medicine students have completed
their studies and become qualified doctors in the past decade. In
1990, the Ministry of Personnel, the Ministry of Public Health,
and the State Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine
issued a joint decision on traditional Chinese medicine education,
and about 1,021 experts became teachers to 1,562 students the same
year.
</P>
<P>
The paper notes that most traditional Chinese medicine students
have obtained their teachers' expertise, and even made innovations
in some treatment methods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
