<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Fewer Recorded Crime Offenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Total recorded crimes in New
Zealand dropped from 461,677 offenses in 1998 to 438,074 in 1999,
representing a drop of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to crime statistics issued Thursday by the New
Zealand Police, decreases in recorded crimes include: violent
offending, robbery, minor assaults, sexual offenses, sexual
violation, drugs, anti-social crimes, and dishonesty crimes.
Burglary reduced by 5.5 percent or 4,020 fewer offenses than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The 5.1 percent drop followed a decrease of 2.5 percent in 1998
and the resolution rate for investigations improved by one percent
to 38.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
After learning the news, New Zealand Minister of Police George
Hawkins issued a statement, saying it is always encouraging to see
the incidence of recorded crime reducing and he wishes to
congratulate the work of all police staff for their efforts in
fighting crimes.
</P>
<P>
"It is excellent that recorded crime is down. Now is the time
to solve more crimes and arrest criminals," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
