<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Burundi to Press for Early Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Burundi peace facilitator
Nelson Mandela will pay his first official visit to Burundi Friday
in a new bid to find a breakthrough in the long-running peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The former South African president will try to persuade the
Tutsi- dominated army to open up to Hutus to pave the way for a
long expected peace agreement, the spokesman of the facilitation
team Brigadier General Hashim Mbita was quoted as saying by
Thursday's Tanzanian newspaper The Guardian.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of Mandela's visit to Burundi is mainly to have talks
with the army," Mbita said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his one-day tour of war-ravaged tiny central African state,
Mandela will be accompanied by his aides from the Mwalimu Nyerere
Foundation and Father Matteo Zuppi, the chairman of committee III
on defense and security formed in the ongoing peace talks.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time for Mandela to visit Burundi since
he took on the mantle of Tanzanian former president Julius Nyerere
as international facilitator to Burundian civil war last November.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has, as a precondition to visit Burundi, asked
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya to release all political
prisoners and dismantle the regroupment camps to free the
civilians staying there.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian army had forced about 300,000 mainly Hutu
civilians from the areas surrounding the capital Bujumbura into
about 60 camps since last September to clear the way for
government operations against the armed Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
Burundi promised in January to close some of the camps but had
failed to do so citing security concerns, though reports said that
President Buyoya inspected two of the camps ahead of Mandela's
visit.
</P>
<P>
Since the latest round of peace talks in March in Tanzanian
northern town of Arusha, all the 19 Burundian parties have been
discussing a draft peace agreement produced by Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The two main rebel groups, the Front for Defence of Democracy
or FDD and the National Liberation Front, have agreed to take part
in the future talks, a latest result of Mandela's mediation.
</P>
<P>
Burundi's civil war began after Tutsi soldiers assassinated the
country' s first democratically elected president, Melchior
Ndadaye, an ethnic Hutu in 1993. Since then Hutu rebels have
fought a rural insurgency campaign against the Tutsi-dominated
army and around 200,000 people, most of them civilians, have lost
their lives.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, which began in Arusha in June 1998, are
currently taking place in four committees, dealing respectively
with the nature of the Burundi conflict, democracy and good
governance, peace and security, economic reconstruction and
return of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Company Reports Profit up 47 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Apple Computer Inc. Wednesday
reported a 47-percent growth in profit for its fiscal second
quarter, much higher than expected, as its new PowerBook and
PowerMac G4 machines sold strongly.
</P>
<P>
Not including one-time gains from Apple's sale of its holdings
in another company, the Cupertino, the California-based computer
maker reported that its second quarter net income rose by 72
percent to 160 million U.S. dollars from 93 million dollars in the
same period in 1999, according to news release from the company.
</P>
<P>
On a per share basis, its earnings rose 47 percent to 88 cents
from 60 cents. The analyst expectation for Apple's second-quarter
earnings was 81 cents per share, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
Revenue rose 27 percent to 1.94 billion dollars from 1.53
billion dollars. About 400 million dollars of Apple's second-
quarter revenue came from sales made through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
Including one-time gains, Apple's net income rose to 233
million dollars, or 1.28 dollars per share, from 135 million
dollars, or 84 cents per share, in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts noted that the popularity of Apple's iMac,
iBook, PowerBook, and PowerMac G4 computers have enabled the
company to have unit growth that is 2.5 times higher than the
industry average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing's Earnings Fall in First Quarter Because of Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co. Wednesday reported
that its first-quarter earnings fell 11 percent as a 40-day
engineers' strike slashed commercial jet deliveries and revenues,
but the world's biggest aerospace company still beat reduced Wall
Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
According to news release from the Seattle-based company, net
income for the first quarter dropped to 418 million U.S. dollars,
or 48 cents a share, from 469 million dollars, or 50 cents a share,
in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial had estimated
profits at 35 cents a share, down from a consensus forecast of 56
cents before the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in
Aerospace began a strike on February 8.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, hailed the first-quarter report as a sign
that the world's largest aircraft maker would likely recover
quickly from the loss caused by the strike.
</P>
<P>
"Two years ago this type of strike would have put the
organization into mass chaos," said analyst Bill Fiala at Edward D.
Jones. "This indicates that management has gotten its act together
on the operations side for the first time in a long time," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Boeing said revenues fell 31 percent to 9.9 billion dollars
from 14.4 billion dollars a year earlier and would have totaled
about 12.5 billion dollars if not for the strike, which trimmed
first-quarter commercial jet deliveries to 75 from its pre-strike
target of 125. Boeing delivered 148 jets in the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
With its engineers back at work, Boeing is striving to get back
on track and meet its 2000 target of 490 commercial jet deliveries,
including a target of 175 to 180 deliveries in the second quarter.
In the first 18 days of April, Boeing delivered 27 airplanes.
</P>
<P>
"Our first priority is getting our customers what they need. We
will be essentially back to our original planned delivery schedule
by the end of the second quarter," said Chairman Phil Condit, who
believes his company can only expect modest revenue growth over
the next three years but plans to continue to boost profitability.
</P>
<P>
Faced with a cyclical market slowdown after delivering a record
620 jets in 1999, Boeing has sought to wring more profits out of
its revenue base, partly through productivity improvements and job
cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
