<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use Nuclear Power in Central Heating System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to provide
heating service using nuclear power in the city of Shenyang in
northeast China's Liaoning Province. And if successful, the major
industrial base will probably become the first city in the world
to apply nuclear in such a field.
</P>
<P>
The project, which has just been approved by the State
Planning Development Commission, will need 1.4 billion yuan (about
168 million U.S. dollars) for the construction of two low-
temperature nuclear reactors. Major funding will come from the
local sources.
</P>
<P>
When the project is completed, over 10 million sq.m. area, or
one-seventh of the city's total heating area, will be provided
with central heating.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua University is the developer of the new reactor, which
is based entirely on Chinese technology.
</P>
<P>
"It astonishes me," "Too dangerous, better not start first in
our city," "Why not have a try? it brings warmth without pollution,
" were some of the reactions of the local people.
</P>
<P>
Ma Xuquan of the Institute of Nuclear Research at the Qinghua
University said the chances of an accident at such a nuclear
reactor will be nil, as it can automatically slow down the
reaction speed when the accumulated heat reaches a set security
limit.
</P>
<P>
Besides the proposed Shenyang project, China is building its
first high-temperature gas-cooled reactor in the suburbs of
Beijing, with an investment of 250 million yuan (about 30 million
US dollars), to provide electricity to the city. This reactor was
also developed by Qinghua University. Several cities including
Shanghai have made plans to install similar facilities.
</P>
<P>
Freezing temperatures, 11.5 degrees Celsius below zero on
average in winter, makes the heating period in Shenyang well over
four months long, and thus coal burning has been the main cause of
air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Currently, coal accounts for 75 percent of China's energy
consumption, creating serious environmental problems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power is economical, efficient, and eco-friendly, and a
good solution to the problem, said an official from China National
Nuclear Corp.
</P>
<P>
The government announced this month that China will focus on
developing advanced, safe, and economical nuclear reactors with
its own intellectual property rights rather than merely relying on
foreign technologies.
</P>
<P>
China has built nuclear power plants in Zhejiang, Guangdong,
and Jiangsu provinces, but the main technologies were imported
from foreign countries, including France and Russia. One of the
consequences is that nuclear technology can not be widely applied.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear industry took shape in the 1950s, and the
country set off its first nuclear bomb in 1964. Since the early
1980s, the sector has been accelerating its efforts to shift from
military production to civilian application, and this sector is
rapidly becoming a major powerhouse in the national economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
