<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Environment for Western China Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese forestry experts have
called for more emphasis on improving the ecology of the country'
s vast western region in the wake of seven consecutive sandstorms
which hit northern China this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 experts from the Chinese Academy of Forestry
Science (CAFS), the State Forestry Administration, and the Beijing
Forestry University gathered in Beijing yesterday to discuss how
best to prevent future sandstorms, according to today's People's
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The experts noted that though people can do little about
droughts and strong winds, they should do their utmost to prevent
expanding desertification.
</P>
<P>
At present, China, especially its western region, is suffering
from a deteriorating ecological environment because of excessive
logging, grazing, and other misuses of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the forest area of most of western China is
sparse, with the coverage rate for the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region only 0.79 percent, and 0.35 percent for Qinghai Province, 1.
54 percent for Ningxia, 4.33 percent for Gansu and 5.84 percent
for the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also show that over the past few decades
desertification in the country has been deteriorating rather than
improving.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1980s, China's desert land expanded at an average
rate of 1,560 square kilometers a year. This figure rose to 2,100
square kilometers a year in the 1980s, and to 2,460 square
kilometers in 1994.
</P>
<P>
So far, China's deserts have grown to nearly 1.7 million
square kilometers, or about 18 percent of the country's total
landscape, and a majority of these deserts are located in the
western region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
