<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outbound Thai Tourists Flow Expected to Return to Pre-crisis Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of outbound Thai
tourists is expected to reach 1.8 million this year, a return to
pre-economic crisis level, the Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This would equal the peak outbound tourist flow recorded in
1996, Pradech Phayakvichien, governor of the Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In January, some 120,000 Thais went overseas, which was close
to the January 1996 record of 129,000, Pradech said.
</P>
<P>
The number of outbound Thai tourists dropped to 1.6 million in
1997 and 1.4 million in 1998. However, signs of economic recovery
pushed the number up to 1.6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
"But spending and the length of stay are decreasing, which
indicates Thais are increasingly cost-conscious when travelling
abroad," said the governor.
</P>
<P>
Currently, average daily spending per head for outbound Thai
tourists is 3,000 baht (80 U.S. dollars), compared with more than
5,000 baht (133 dollars) before the crisis.
</P>
<P>
During the economic boom, the average length of stay for
outbound Thai tourists was nine days but now it has been shortened.
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, most Thais were now travelling mainly within
Asia, Pradech said, citing Hong Kong and China's mainland as the
most popular destinations for Thai tourists.
</P>
<P>
Pradech pointed out that travelling abroad would not harm the
country's economy if Thais could gain useful knowledge and not
spending excessively on shopping and gambling.
</P>
<P>
However, The TAT is continuing with its campaign to promote
domestic travel as well, the governor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
