<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Law, Economics Faculty to Expand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Law and Economics
Faculty is being reorganized, additional courses included and is
to be turned into a full university, according to Cambodia's state
news agency report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The institution will this year start three more faculties -
management science, banking and finance and commerce and
accounting.
</P>
<P>
The faculty has been offering four-year bachelor programs in
law and economics, in addition to a one-year bachelor course on
business administration for those who have completed the third
year in any faculty.
</P>
<P>
This year, the faculty also plans to introduce post graduate
courses in economic management leading to masters degree for those
with bachelor's degrees in economics, law and engineering.
</P>
<P>
The faculty, founded in 1948 at the initiative of then Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, now has an enrollment of 2,875.
</P>
<P>
Dean Yuok Ngoy said the faculty was preparing to turn itself
into a university due to the increase in the number of students
and faculties.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia now has 9 public institutes and 2 private institutes
that provide training on 62 skills.
</P>
<P>
The royal government of Cambodia attaches great importance to
education, taking it as a key to accelerate the economic growth
and alleviate the poverty.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than one third of Cambodian people are illiterate
and had no access to education at all. Only 20 percent has primary
education and 4 percent has lower secondary education.
</P>
<P>
Considerable efforts have been deployed by the government to
increase investment in this sector by increasing budget
allocations for education, mobilizing foreign aid and encouraging
contribution from the society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
