<HEADLINE> Thai Women Untie Their Apron Strings: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to the popular myth that
women belong to the kitchen, 70 percent of Thai women are in the
active workforce, although they receive 20 percent less pay than
their male counterparts, the Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a study conducted by labor academic Worawit
Charoenlert of Chulalongkorn University as saying that the rate of
participation of Thai women in economic production was second only
to Chinese women, 80 percent of whom are in the workforce.
</P>
<P>
"Based on international studies of females in the workforce, we
can say that Thai women are the second hardest-working
contributors to the economic well-being in the world," Worawit
said.
</P>
<P>
The study also indicates the majority of Thai women have to
assume a dual responsibility as the family's second breadwinner as
well as housewife and mother.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, women form the main unskilled
workforce. They are often the victims of occupational hazards that
come with labor-intensive industries, such as respiratory
illnesses from textile production and lead poisoning from
electronics assembly plants.
</P>
<P>
Female workers in Thailand have also been the main driving
force in demanding increased work safety while male workers have
focused on pay raises, the study notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Commit 1,250 Million U.S. Dollars to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The bilateral and multilateral
donors in the Nepal Development Forum (NDF) meeting which
concluded in Paris Wednesday agreed to extend 1,250 million U.S.
dollars to Nepal during 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the World Bank at the
end of the meeting, monitored here Thursday, the donor countries
had strictly tied such assistance to Nepal's progress on reforms.
</P>
<P>
"Nepal's development partners reaffirmed their assistance to
Nepal in addressing the challenge of poverty reduction and
economic growth and the level of assistance in 2000-2001 will
range from current level up to 1,250 million U.S. dollars," the
release said.
</P>
<P>
Donors had made a pledge of one billion U.S. dollars in
assistance to Nepal in a similar meeting held four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The donors, however, emphasized that actual levels of
assistance will reflect progress in policy and institutional
reforms and improvements in aid effectiveness, said the release,
adding the levels could even be higher if the pace of reform is
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here Thursday, discussions on
poverty alleviation strategy was another important agenda other
than reform during the meeting in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The donors endorsed the Poverty Alleviation Strategy proposed
by the Nepali government and agreed to contribute significantly in
this regard, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The NDF meeting was participated by 23 bilateral and
multilateral donors assisting Nepal's development effort. The
meeting, which was supposed to be held every two years, was held
after four years due to the political instability in Nepal in the
last couple of years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
