<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar FM on World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The world economy continues to be
marked by uncertainty and imbalances as well as the continuing
marginalization of developing countries in this era of globalizing
world, said Myanmar Foreign Minister U Win Aung.
</P>
<P>
In his statement delivered at the just-ended plenary meeting
of the South Summit of the group of 77 (G-77) held in Havana, Cuba,
U Win Aung blamed that the benefits of economic growth and
prosperity to the world economy, derived from globalization, have
not been enjoyed equitably by many developing countries,
especially the least developed among them.
</P>
<P>
He called for adoption of a new approach to international
development cooperation based on growth, stability and equity with
full participation and integration of developing countries into
the globalizing world economy.
</P>
<P>
On financial matters, he emphasized the need to address the
serious deficiencies of the existing international structure
governing finance, trade and development, calling for efforts to
establish more stringent rules and regulations on short-term
capital flows in order to maintain and promote stability in the
international financial system.
</P>
<P>
He warned that there is a tendency on the part of the developed
countries to take decisions that affect the world economy without
giving adequate consideration to the interests of developing
countries and the wind of democratic change that swept across the
world in the political arena have not yet reached the
international institutions, including the United Nations and the
Brettonwoods.
</P>
<P>
He believed that sustained economic growth and development,
particularly of developing countries, must be the main objective
to be pursued as a priority by the international community in
managing the globalizing world economy.
</P>
<P>
Regarding global trade negotiation, U Win Aung stressed the
need to give assistance to the developing and least developed
countries which are already overburdened with the implementation
of the existing World Trade Organization Agreement, taking into
account development dimension while ensuring that these countries
are well prepared to take part in future multilateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need that the pace and areas of further
trade liberalization should respond to the priorities of the
developing countries in accordance with the principle of
progressive liberalization of international trading system.
</P>
<P>
He urged the developed countries to fulfill their commitments
to special and differential treatment in favor of developing
countries by opening up their markets and granting duty-free and
quota-free access to the exports to the least developed among them.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the inability to resolve the problems of the
developed countries will deepen the marginalization of these
countries and will further widen the gap between the developed and
the developing countries, urging developed countries to further
reduce tariff barriers for goods from developing countries and
also make a concerted effort to prevent quality standards from
being used unfairly.
</P>
<P>
He called for remaining firm in resisting the renewed attempt
by some countries of the North to link labor standards with
multilateral trade rules, regarding those attempts as a new form
of protectionism with a hidden motive to damage the rare
comparative advantage of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
On the part of Myanmar, he said, the country particularly
values economic relations with its partners in the South, wanting
to see concrete steps to strengthen cooperation among developing
countries in a wide range of areas such as trade, investment,
technical cooperation, industrialization, energy, food and
agriculture, technology, capacity building and human resources
development.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Myanmar's appreciation over the role played by the
G-77 and China in strengthening international cooperation for
development, reiterating the country's commitment to the
continuing validity and relevance of the objectives and principles
of the G-77 and readiness to cooperate with others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
