<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hostage Crisis Escalating in Southern Philippines By Pan Jiaxu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The hostage crisis in the southern
Philippines has been escalating after the extremist Abu Sayyaf
group executed two of their 29 hostages Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sabaya, spokesman of the Muslim rebel group, announced the
execution Wednesday afternoon, saying that they will kill more
hostages every time the Presidential Palace "makes a negative
statement."
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf abducted more than 50 civilians, mostly teachers
and school children, on March 20 in the village of Tumahubong in
Basilan in a bid to ward off pursuit by government troops
following a raid on an army camp.
</P>
<P>
Some of the hostages have reportedly been freed in exchange for
food and medicine. The remaining 29 hostages are believed to
include 22 children, several teachers and a Chatholic priest.
</P>
<P>
According to the demands uttered by the Abu Sayyaf in their
letters to the government, the three U.S.-held militants include
Ramzi Yousef, the mastermind of the 1993 bombing of the U.S. World
Trade Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
The other two are Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman, convicted for
conspiracy in a plot to bomb U.S. landmarks, and Abu Haider,
jailed in California and believed to be teacher of the late Abu
Sayyaf founder Abdubakar Janjalani.
</P>
<P>
But reports said the Philippine government has ruled out any
compromise with the Abu Sayyaf, one of the two Muslim groups
fighting for an Islamic state in the southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre said the Philippine
government has not asked the United States to release the
terrorists "because certainly that is legally impossible."
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said the government will exhaust all peaceful means,
but he also warned the rebels "to be prepared, because there is
always a limit."
</P>
<P>
The government also said the military forces will launch attack
against the extremist Abu Sayyaf group if the report of two
hostages' death turns true, the ABS-CBN news channel said Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
In response to the reported killing of two hostages, Defense
Secretary Orlando Mercado said that if the Abu Sayyaf killed
hostages indeed, the government has no choice but to attack the
rebel group.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the government has been holding back rescue
efforts because this will put the lives of the hostages at risk.
</P>
<P>
"If (the execution) reports are indeed true, the Abu Sayyaf has
just thrown away any leverage it has with the government," Mercado
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Abu Sayyaf even threatened to "kidnap or
kill" Americans in the country if their demand was not met.
</P>
<P>
As a response, the U.S. Embassy here said they will continue to
work and protect their citizens in the country. Meanwhile the
Embassy advised Americans to avoid visiting Basilan, some 880
kilometers south of Manila.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 100,000 Americans living in the
Philippines, with an undetermined number of them living in the
southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
National Police spokesman Nicanor Barolome said police and
military forces have increased visibility to ensure the safety of
people, both locals and foreigners, in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Armed Forces said it had already lined up
several "military options" to rescue the hostages and was prepared
to risk civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
"We have several military options and these are just waiting to
be activated," said Armed Forces spokesman Rafel Romero. He did
not elaborate on the options.
</P>
<P>
The military is believed to be biding time until the Basilan-
based Crisis Management Committee CMC) exhausts all attempts to
resolve the month-long hostage crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada has reportedly asked the CMC to
persuade the Abu Sayyaf to "act within reason and within legal and
moral possibilities."
</P>
<P>
As this developed, the parents and relatives of the hostages
have been staying at the Christian Formation Center in Isabela,
Basilan, waiting for the release of the captives.
</P>
<P>
They said that if the government could not do anything to stop
the execution, they would make their own move.
</P>
<P>
Reports said their move is to go to the Abu Sayyaf's Camp
Abdujarak in Mt. Mahadji and offer themselves in exchange for the
freedom of their loved ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
