<HEADLINE> Cyclone Crosses North-Western Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The category four cyclone named
as Rosita crossed the northern West Australian coast Thursday at 1.
20 a.m. local time, 40km south of Broome.
</P>
<P>
Trees were uprooted and roofs blown off houses as it crossed,
the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Broome said the town experienced strong winds and
rain but no casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
So there was a lot of noise, a lot of rain, a lot of trees
being blown around and it was quite an extraordinary experience,
they said.
</P>
<P>
There were reports on roofs being blown off in the town and
some ceilings collapsing and unrooted trees crashing down on
houses and cars. The historic precinct of Chinatown, which
features museums and other relics of Broome's famed pearling
history, suffered flooding.
</P>
<P>
One of the most significant casualties was Cable Beach, world
famous for its gleaming white sands and its camel rides, which
took a pounding from huge and incessant waves, its sands being
stripped to expose rock underneath. 
</P>
</TEXT>
