<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Language Enrichment Project for Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a book
based language enrichment project to develop the habit of reading
and popularize reference based learning among school children, the
official Daily News said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The project is being implemented at primary level targeting
young students because when the habit is inculcated from the early
stages it develops with the growth," the World Bank consultant
Warwick Elley, who is in charge of the project, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The project, to cost 1280 million rupees (17.37 million U.S.
dollars) funded by the World Bank, is a joint collaboration of the
Ministry of Education and Higher Education and the bank, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the project 400 primary school teachers have concluded a
special training in methods to improve the reading habit among
students.
</P>
<P>
According to the project, 2,000 new school libraries are being
established and another 2,000 existing libraries will be
modernized replacing outdated reading material with read-worthy
publications and new audio visual equipment.
</P>
<P>
The supply of this material has already started as a pilot
project at provincial level with 25 schools from each province
having been selected, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
