<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Mekong Countries Sign Navigation Agreement in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The governments of China, Laos,
Myanmar and Thailand Thursday officially reached an agreement in
Myanmar's border town of Tachilek on commercial navigation on the
Lancang-Mekong River.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of their respective governments, Chinese Minister of
Communications Huang Zhendong, Lao Minister of Communication,
Transport, Post and Construction Phao Bounnaphol, Myanmar Minister
of Transport Major-General Hla Myint Swe and Thai Minister of
Transport and Communications Suthep Thuegsuban signed the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Lancang-Mekong river will be opened
for commercial navigation among the four signatory countries one
year after the endorsement and vessels of any signatory nation are
entitled to sail freely between Simao in China and Luangprabang in
Laos.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the ports to be opened by the four
signatory countries for commercial navigation on the Lancang-
Mekong river total 14, of which four are from China, six from Laos,
two each from Myanmar and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will enter into force for five years from the
date of signature and it will be automatically renewed for
successive periods of three years unless a signatory country gives
notice in writing to terminate the agreement three months before
the expiry of its validity.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement is aimed at developing on the
Lancang-Mekong river the international passenger and cargo
transportation, trade and tourism among the four signatory
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Government Bans Internet Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Prime Minister
John Howard threatened Thursday the federal government would
pursue a total ban on Internet gambling.
</P>
<P>
Some states in Australia are to legislate for Internet gambling
in bit to increase tax revenue and refused a 12-month moratorium
proposal from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
"We think there's too much gambling in this country already,
and it's far easier to stop something starting than trying to wind
back something that's been there for years," the prime minister
told Melbourne radio 3AW.
</P>
<P>
"If you have a moratorium, it can't happen during that period
of time and during that moratorium we wanted to investigate the
feasibility of a permanent prohibition on the Internet," he said.
</P>
