<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, DPRK Sign Partial Visa Abolition Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) signed here Thursday the partial
visa abolition agreement to facilitate the entry of the citizens
of the two sides into their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by Malaysian Foreign Ministry
Secretary-General Abdul Kadir and DPRK Ambassador Kim Ja Ryong to
Malaysia on behalf of their respective governments, citizens of
two sides can enter each other's country without visa for no more
than 30 days for the purpose of official duties, business trips,
vacation, sports and attending conference or seminars.
</P>
<P>
Both Abdul Kadir and Kim Ja Ryong said on the occasion that the
agreement marks a milestone in the bilateral relations between
Malaysia and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Both sides hoped that with the signing of the agreement,
friendly relations between the two countries, particularly in the
areas of trade and tourism will be further enhanced.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the DPRK embassy here, Malaysia is
the third ASEAN country to sign such agreement with the DPRK which
already signed similar agreements with Vietnam and Laos.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and the DPRK established diplomatic relations in June
1973. The total trade between the two countries grew to 29.65
million ringgit (7.8 million U.S. dollars) in 1999 from 9.66
million ringgit (2.54 million U.S. dollars) in 1998, according to
official figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
