<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Sets 10-Year Economic Development Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan
Province has mapped out a ten-year development plan, aiming to
build the province into an economic strong power in western China
in ten years.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Governor Zhang Zhongwei said recently that the province
wants its gross domestic products (GDP) to catch up with the
national average level by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
In ecological construction, Sichuan will work hard to reduce
the amount of sands washed into the Yangtze River by more than 50
percent and increase its vegetation coverage to over 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In social development, the province will make efforts to
control its annual population growth rate under 0.7 percent and
make rural average per capita income reach the national average by
2010.
</P>
<P>
In ten years, the province will expand its urbanization to 30
percent and will have established a comprehensive social security
system with most urban residents leading a well-off life, he added.
</P>
<P>
To meet the target, Zhang said Sichuan will first accelerate
its infrastructure construction to pave way for future economic
take-off.
</P>
<P>
It will also make further efforts to protect the province's
natural forests and to convert more farmlands to forests and
grassland, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan is playing an important role in the country's strategic
program to develop western China, he said, citing the facts that
its population is 30 percent of the total in the western region
which covers nine provinces and one municipality; Its GDP accounts
for the region's 31 percent while its retail sales taking up 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
Despite its abundant natural resources and market advantage,
the province has yet to make further efforts to cultivate its
development potentials, the governor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
