<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Act of Terrorism Ruled out in Philippine Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
ruled out an act of terrorism in Wednesday's air crash that
claimed all the 131 lives on board of the Air Philippines Flight
541, the nation's leading TV channel ABS-ABN said Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
An official of the nation's air transportation authority was
quoted as saying in ABS-CBN's morning news report that it was not
"an act of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary Jacinto Ortega of the Philippine Air
Transportation Office (ATO) told a press briefing Wednesday night
that human error may have caused the air tragedy in southern city
of Davao Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Ortega said their initial findings showed that Flight 541 pilot
Avilusmano Catipay "misapproached" the plane's descent to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
The initial findings run counter to one of the earlier reported
possibilities for the cause of the crash -- sabotage, especially
in the wake of reported threats of terrorists to wage war against
the government by bombing public facilities.
</P>
<P>
Ortega said the plane's blackbox has been recovered and the ATO
hoped that it will reveal the situation during the final minutes
before the crash.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 737-200 with 124 passengers and 7 crew members on
board crashed at around 7:05 a.m. local time Wednesday in Mount
Camanlangan of Samal Island, some 1,000 kilometers south of Manila.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated passenger plane left the Philippine capital of
Manila at around 5:20 a.m. and was expected to reach Davao City at
6:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
As of 6:56 a.m., however, Davao airport officials said
Philippine Airlines Flight 509 had yet to clear Runway 05, the
same landing area which Flight 541 was supposed to take.
</P>
<P>
Assessing the situation, Catipay requested the Davao airport
tower for another landing area and the plane reportedly had to
circle the Davao International Airport.
</P>
<P>
At 7:03 a.m., the Davao tower lost contact with the Air
Philippines Boeing 737. Two helicopters confirmed the crash site
two minutes later or 5.5 kilometers away from the airport runway.
</P>
<P>
As of Thursday morning, rescuers have recovered 83 bodies from
the crash site but no survivors have been found at all.
</P>
<P>
An Air Philippines official earlier claimed the plane was given
its normal maintenance check before taking off and that no
abnormalities were found.
</P>
<P>
Also, the Philippine Atmospheric Geophysical Astronomical
Services Administration (Pagasa) confirmed weather conditions at
the time of the crash were good and that there was no problem with
visibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Investigate East Timor Human Rights Abuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA,April 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Attorney General's
Office (AGO) Wednesday set up a team to officially investigate
allegations of human rights abuses in East Timor, in the months
before and after it voted to secede from Indonesia on August 30,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The 64-member investigation team comprises 38 officials from
the AGO, 10 from the Military Police, six officers from the
National Police Force and 10 officials from the Home Ministry.
Deputy Attorney for Special Crimes M.A. Rachman serves as
executive chairman of the team.
</P>
<P>
Another 15-member team of experts was also appointed to consult
and review the work of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Marzuki Darusman underlined the importance of
the work of the team, pointing out that not only would the nation
be watching but also the whole world.
</P>
<P>
"The handling of human rights violations in East Timor is
something new and sets a historical precedence in our law
enforcement. The investigation has the potential to show the
international community that Indonesia has a judicial system and
law enforcement that can uphold the law," he was quoted by the
Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The team will have three months to report its findings, with
the possibility of further three-month extensions.
</P>
<P>
The findings will become the basis for the AGO to decide to
pursue, or drop, charges against the alleged rights violators.
</P>
<P>
At an August 30 ballot last year organized by the United
Nations, the people of East Timor overwhelmingly rejected
Indonesian rule, setting off a wave of killing and destruction by
pro-Jakarta militias backed by elements of the Indonesian Military
(TNI), which was then headed by General Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
A National Commission of Human Rights inquiry presented a
report to the AGO in February concluding that several top military
officers should be held accountable for the violence including
Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Observer Thursday quoted sources as saying that
the investigation team will summon several military officers on
Monday for questioning on the atrocities. The team will also
question several top officers, including Wiranto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
