<HEADLINE> Australian Prime Minister Criticizes Heroin Injecting Room </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard Thursday criticized the plan to set up heroin injecting
rooms in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
He told radio 3AW that injecting rooms sent a message to the
community that drug-taking was acceptable.
</P>
<P>
The Victorian state government Wednesday said it would
introduce legislation in state parliament during this session to
establish injecting centers in five municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The New South Wales state and the Australian Capital Territory
have finished legislating process to open heroin injecting rooms.
It was claimed that professionally controlled injecting could
reduce death rate caused by overdose.
</P>
<P>
Howard warned that although such injecting rooms were not
against federal law, Victoria could expect no help from the
Federal Government.
</P>
<P>
"I should make it plain to the Victorian government, as I have
to the New South Wales and ACT governments, that they will get no
help of any kind from the federal government," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am very strongly of the view that the weakness in the past
has been that all states have not provided enough resources to
help people who want to break the habit and get the medical and
psychological help they need," he criticized, adding that "I think
injecting rooms convey to the community a view that, well, it's
okay; let's not try and rehabilitate, let's just accept."
</P>
<P>
He urged the state Liberals to block the Victorian legislation
in the upper house.  
</P>
</TEXT>
