<HEADLINE> Bosnia Sees Improvement in Financial Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Central Bank announced
Wednesday in Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia and Herzegovina, that the
country's financial situation improved last year as the currency
and retail prices remained basically stabled, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Peter Nicholl, president of the Bosnian Central Bank said the
retail price in the Muslem-Croat Federation remained stable on the
whole with a slight decline from the 1998, and its inflation rate
was negative one percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the retail price in Serbia increased gradually with
its inflation rate standing at 14 percent, Peter said.
</P>
<P>
Last year the Bosnian Cental Bank gained 12 million Bosnian
convertible marks (about 6 million U.S. dollars), doubling that in
1998. The profit of the bank went up to 4 million Bosnian
exchanged marks (two million dollars) from 80,000 Bosnian
convertible marks (40,000 dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign trade of Bosnia was less optimistic. Its
exports amounted to 1.03 billion convertible marks (about 515
million dollars) last year, while its imports valued at 5.18
billion convertible marks (2.59 billion dollars). Bosnia has
incurred a foreign trade deficit of 4.155 billion convertible
marks (2 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
