<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno: Court Rule not Bar Transferring Elian to Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno said Wednesday that the Justice Department will abide by an
appeals court rule over the case of Elian Gonzalez, but stressed
that the rule will not prevent the government from transferring
the six-year-old Cuban boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
Reno made the statement in Oklahoma City in response to a
decision earlier in the day by the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals
in Atlanta, which extended an injunction order to keep the boy in
the United States pending an appeal.
</P>
<P>
The court panel decided to bar anyone from attempting to remove
the young Cuban shipwreck survivor from the country.
</P>
<P>
The panel announced that they recognized the government's
authority over immigration matters, but adding that "we fail to
see how an injunction in the case infringes upon the congressional
power."
</P>
<P>
"The 11th Circuit's order, as I say, prevents him from leaving
the country while the appeal is pending. We will abide by that,"
Reno said.
</P>
<P>
However, Reno made it clear that the court rule "does not
preclude me from placing Elian in his father's care while he is in
the United States."
</P>
<P>
The boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, arrived in the United
States on April 6 to fight for the custody of his son with his
distant relatives in Miami. The Immigration and Naturalization
Service (INS) ruled that the boy belongs to his father.
</P>
<P>
"We are still reviewing the court's decision, for I have just
had the chance to look at it as I have come off the plane. We are
going to take and consider all our options and take the course of
action that we deem appropriate under the circumstances," Reno
added.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 last year near a shipwreck
after his mother and 10 others were drowned when their boat
capsized in the sea off Florida and later was sent to his
relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
The appeals court order temporarily blocked anyone from taking
Elian out of the country until it decides whether to hear the
asylum claims.
</P>
<P>
Reno said that the appeals court's decision addressed the
asylum issue only, but did not deal with who cares for the child
while he is in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The immigration laws clearly call for a child to be placed in
the care of a parent, in preference to a more distant relative,
while the child's immigration status is being resolved," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
