<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Join Railways along Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 20 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to build a 420-
kilometer-long railway to effect the linking of a railway
thoroughfare along the country's longest river of Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The railway is designed to run through the country's most
rugged areas to connect Yidu City, close to the Three Gorges Dam
in central China's Hubei Province, with southwest China's
Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The 11.7 billion yuan (1.4 billion U.S. dollars) project will
make it possible for train to run directly from Shanghai to
Chongqing along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
For people living in the western mountains of Hubei Province,
construction of the railway could be no better news. "That is what
we have been aspiring for almost a century," said Guo Daxiao, head
of the Enshi Tujia and Miao Autonomous Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
The traffic inconvenience has become a herculean hinder to the
local economic development. All the eight counties under its
jurisdiction are among the poorest counties in China. Currently
about two percent of its 3.8 million people are still poverty-
stricken. Local people have been praying for railway as they do
for rain in drought season.
</P>
<P>
The plan of building the railway in this rough country first
came into being in 1903. A railway company was formed in the
following year with Zhan Tianyou as the general engineer. Zhan had
studied in the United States and was an authentic expert on
railways.
</P>
<P>
The construction work, however, was suspended by war in 1926
with only dozens of kilometers of roadbed and seven kilometers'
rail paved.
</P>
<P>
The re-launching of the project is partly attributed to China's
recent strategy to develop its vast western region. Enshi, the
youngest autonomous prefecture established in 1983, was
fortunately included in the grand development strategy.
</P>
<P>
"Improving infrastructure including a convenient traffic plays
an increasingly important role in absorbing foreign investment,"
Guo said, believing that the railway parallel to the Yangtze River
would bring more business opportunities to Enshi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another railway between Chongqing and Huaihua City
of central China's Hunan Province will also be constructed soon.
This railway will pass by Enshi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
