<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Fruit Growers Use Pheromone to Kill Injurious Insects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Australian fruit growers kill
injurious insects with pheromone dispensers.
</P>
<P>
According to The Age Thursday, they are putting tiny pheromone
dispensers in their orchards and fields which mimic the scents
that female insects and moths produce to attract males. As a
result, the male becomes completely overwhelmed by many pheromones
flying through the air and finds it impossible to get hold of a
female.
</P>
<P>
"The poor old male runs around looking for a female and every
time he gets on a scent he ends up on a piece of plastic," a
farmer was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sexual trickery is part of the Integrated Pest Management
strategy developed by the Australian government's Horticultural
Research and Development Corporation. More and more fruit and
vegetable growers no longer have to rely on pesticides and are
reporting greater yields while consumers are getting fruit and
vegetables free of chemical residue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
