<HEADLINE> Anti-Govt Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 34 members from three
anti-government armed groups in Myanmar surrendered to the
government last month, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These members of the Shan-State United Revolutionary Army (SURA)
, All Burma Students' Democratic Front (ABSDF) and Kayin National
Union (KNU) "exchanged arms for peace" at southern, southeast,
eastern, northwestern, coastal and triangle region command areas
respectively between March 1 and 31.
</P>
<P>
They brought along with them a total of 227 rounds of
ammunition, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The SURA is an anti-government Shan ethnic armed group
operating in the northeastern Shan state, while the ABSDF is a
similar students' armed organization operating on the Thai-Myanmar
border and the KNU is the largest anti-government ethnic armed
group operating on the same border for over five decades since the
early days of Myanmar's independence.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups as well as
the Mong Tai Army, led by former drug warlord Khun Sa, have made
peace with the government with cease-fire agreements reached
between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
