<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD Official on Brazil's Export Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. official said
Wednesday that Brazil lacks an effective policy to revive its
export trade.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) Rubens Ricupero said that of the hundred
products growing rapidly in the international trade, none is
included in the Brazilian foreign sales list.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD predicted that Brazil's share in world trade would
remain the same this year when the international trade is expected
to grow 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Brazilian exports, based on primary products, such as steel,
soybean complex, coffee, paper and cellulose, have been stranded
for 20 years," Ricupero told a local news agency.
</P>
<P>
Until the second week of April, Brazilian exports amounted to a
total of 14.053 billion U.S. dollars, 88 million dollars less than
its imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
