<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mafiaboy Bailed Out After Charged With Mischief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 19 (Xinhua) -- A Montreal boy believed to be "
Mafiaboy" was bailed out Wednesday after charged with two counts
of mischief under the Young Offenders Act of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The 15-year-old youngster, who could not be identified because
of his age, was out on condition that he should not be allowed to
use the Internet or frequent computer stores. He can only use a
computer under supervision for school homework, Canadian police
said.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, the teenage boy could face a maximum sentence of
two years in custody and be fined up to 1,000 Canadian dollars (
about 675 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, Police Inspector Yves Roussel told a press
conference in Montreal that "the prosecution intends to
demonstrate before the court that Mafiaboy is responsible for the
denial-of-service attack that was launched for more than four
hours on the 8th of February against the CNN site" and 1,200 CNN-
hosted sites.
</P>
<P>
But he said he didn't believe Mafiaboy was "what we would call
a genius."
</P>
<P>
He said investigators were able to track the suspect in part
because he bragged about his alleged exploit in messages sent to
Internet chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
"This individual, using the nickname Mafiaboy, would have
publicized on many occasions that he was the person responsible
for those attacks," said the officer.
</P>
<P>
What is important is "to let young people know they are not
going to get away with these abuses because of age. More
importantly, we have to renew our efforts to teach children, young
people about cyber-ethics," the police inspector noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the investigation "is still on-going" and "there is an
open possibility that others might be arrested."
</P>
<P>
Between February 7 and 14, hackers launched a series of cyber
attacks against famous Web sites such as Yahoo!, Ebay, CNN, Amazon.
com, Excite and Etrade, causing economic losses of millions of
dollars and triggering security concerns by the Internet industry
and users around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
