<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Steps Up Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region in
southwest China invested 700 million yuan (84 million U.S. dollars)
in highway construction last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Tibet completed the renovation and reconstruction of
several highways, including the renovation project of the Qinghai-
Tibet highway, the Damxung-Lhunzhub-Lhasa highway, and
improvement of the Bamda-Qamdo highway and several sections of the
Sichuan-Tibet highway.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is the only region with no railways among China's 34
provinces, municipalities, and autonomous regions, and depends
mainly on highways to transport goods into and out of the region.
</P>
<P>
This landlocked part of southwestern China has spent a total of
3.6 billion yuan on road construction in the past five years,
providing highway access to over 80 percent of its townships.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, the length of the region's highways is
expected to exceed 25,900 kilometers, linking together all the
villages in Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
