<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Calls for Relic Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A relics protection official has
called for prompt steps to curb the accidental damage done to
cultural relics in urban construction, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The most urgent task for us is to reverse the opinion that we
can simply brush aside the issue of relics protection, and pull
down relics to make way for economic development," said Song
Xinchao, director of the Archaeological Finding Division of the
State Bureau of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
Demolition of relics occurred in urban construction projects,
the majority of which were done out of ignorance of the law and
the significance of relic treasures.
</P>
<P>
The Relics Protection Law, which took effect since 1982,
clearly stated that construction companies are responsible for
protecting relics unearthed in construction areas as well as all
the necessary expenses involved in the protection.
</P>
<P>
"Relics are the common heritage of all Chinese people, and we
want the public to understand that relics protection is the
responsibility of the whole society," Song was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
