<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chelsea and Middlesbrough Charged by FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 19 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer
clubs Chelsea and Middlesbrough have been charged by English F.A.
with failing to control their players.
</P>
<P>
The FA charged the two Premiership clubs following separate
incidents in which players are accused of intimidating match
officials.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea, who were fined 50,000 pounds last week after being
found guilty of the same offence, are back in the dock to explain
the actions of their players at the end of Saturday's game at
Sheffield Wednesday. Middlesbrough have been charged over their
players' reaction to Manchester United's fourth goal in Boro's 4-3
defeat, on Monday April 10, when they thought scorer Quinton
Fortune was offside.
</P>
<P>
Television replays later proved the linesman had made the right
decision.
</P>
<P>
The Middlesbrough charge is laced with irony because it was the
behaviour of Manchester United players after a penalty decision at
Old Trafford, during a game with Boro in January, which prompted
the FA clampdown on intimidation of officials.
</P>
<P>
United's stars, led by Roy Keane and Jaap Stam, hounded referee
Andy D'Urso to the touchline after he had awarded the visitors a
penalty.
</P>
<P>
No action was taken against the Old Trafford club or the
players involved but the FA's new chief executive Adam Crozier
pledged to end the ugly sight of Premiership players screaming in
the faces of referees.
</P>
<P>
Lancaster Gate, while aware of controversially charging
Middlesbrough over an incident relating to the return fixture,
studied video tapes of this month's game at the Riverside Stadium
and decided to act in keeping with the new edict.
</P>
<P>
The FA are unlikely to deduct points from the London club as
they chase a Champions League place, made all the more important
after their exit from Europe at the hands of Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
Middlesbrough, as first-time offenders, are looking at a
smaller
fine if the case against them is proved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
