<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian President Calls for Enhanced Ties Among African States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika here on Thursday called for enhancing the ties among the
African countries to "maximize the capacities of the continent in
the development battle."
</P>
<P>
"The continent is not poor. It has eminent natural and human
resources," he said in his address to the opening ceremony of the
23rd session of African ministers of labour and social affairs.
</P>
<P>
The labour and production force is the only guarantee for
assuming an advanced position among competitors in the
globalization age that is increasingly emerging in various aspects
of international relations, said Bouteflika, also current president
of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
He stressed the important role of the African women in the
development process.
</P>
<P>
On the unemployment problem in Africa, Bouteflika said the
resolution of the problem lies in expanding labor-intensive
investment projects such as free business and traditional
industries that take into account the social privacies of the
vulnerable categories.
</P>
<P>
He called on the African countries to face up to the challenges
and problems to promote the achievements of the last century and
achieve more goals to improve the social conditions and find
practical solutions to the issues on the agenda of the current
session.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating living conditions and spreading poverty in
Africa result mainly from weak investment and slow economic growth
rate, Bouteflika noted. He also blamed the years of drought that
impoverished vast areas of the black continent for deteriorating
the living conditions and exacerbating the unemployment situation.
</P>
<P>
He urged the African countries to expand the channels of open
and direct dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bouteflica called on the international community to
abandon the discriminative view about Africa in terms of human
rights and not to separate the social and economic rights from the
civil and political ones.
</P>
<P>
The two-day session of African ministers of labor and social
affairs attracted representatives of 53 African countries and
delegates of 25 regional and international organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
