<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Army Captures Honduran Fishing Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan Army captured this
week three small fishing boats that had sailed from Honduras and
El Salvador and were fishing in the Gulf of Fonseca in the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan Navy said Thursday that the three canoes were
detained when they were in the zone known as Punta de San Jose on
the Nicaraguan side of the gulf.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf of Fonseca is shared by Honduras, Nicaragua and El
Salvador, and the lack of border markings has caused frequent
captures of fishermen of one of the three countries in the
territorial waters of the other two, and has even caused two armed
conflicts this year.
</P>
<P>
The naval forces of Honduras and Nicaragua accused each other
last February of having provoked shoot-outs between patrol boats
in their waters.
</P>
<P>
Technical missions of the two countries got together on April 7
in Tegucigalpa, the Honduran capital, to listen to the offers of
five companies who offered to sell and install the 14 buoys that
will show the demarcation of the border in the Gulf of Fonseca.
</P>
<P>
However, both governments declared deserted the bidding for the
installation of the buoys in the gulf.
</P>
<P>
The "mother" buoy was placed in 1997 on the borderline between
Honduras and Nicaragua in the gulf, and it is expected that the
other 14 will be installed before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
As in the Pacific, both nations maintain a similar problem in
the Caribbean since November 30 last year, when the Honduran
Congress ratified with Colombia a maritime limits treaty.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua says that this treaty takes from its sovereignty 130,
000 square kilometers of its continental platform in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of American States (OAS) intervened at the
request of the two countries with its mediator Luigi Einaudi, who
facilitated a distention environment to prevent an armed
confrontation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
