<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Major Markets Mixed Pre-Easter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets
closed mostly higher Thursday, bolstered by shares of media, oil,
and tobacco companies as a four-day holiday weekend got under way.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 in London rose 56.3 points, or 0.9 percent, to 6,
241.2, returning to the black after early losses as top media and
drug companies pulled the index higher.
</P>
<P>
SmithKline reported a 15 percent jump in earnings per share to
6.9 pence while Glaxo said turnover in the quarter to end-March
rose 12 percent to 2.125 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300, a broader measure of the region's largest
companies, added 0.8 at 1,589.92. Sub-indexes for tobacco and
media stocks rose, while steel, automotive and technology
companies were lower.
</P>
<P>
Dealers were hard pressed to summon up much enthusiasm as
proceedings wound down ahead of the four-day Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
"There's not really any pattern out there. Compared with the
volatility that's been in the market, it's been very, very quiet,"
said one dealer.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the bourse ended higher as a slew of corporate news --
including disclosure of Dresdner Bank's 3.6 percent stake in
Credit Lyonnais -- lifted the market ahead of the Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 ended up 68.05 or 1.1 percent at 6,234.51 points.
The index has gained 168.80 since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Xetra Dax index eased in light trade ahead of the
Easter weekend as falls by software company SAP and
DaimlerChrysler outweighed gains by most tech stocks and Dresdner
Bank, which climbed on merger speculation.
</P>
<P>
The index ended down 58.76 points, or 0.81 percent, at 7,157.95,
a fall of 56.88 from April 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
