<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Government, ELN Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian government and the
rebel National Liberation Army (ELN) agreed Thursday to establish
a demilitarized zone in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is the first between the government and that
armed guerrilla group, the second in importance after the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC). The authorities are
holding peace talks with it.
</P>
<P>
The zone of dissension will be formed by three municipalities:
Yong Do (Antioquia), San Pablo, and Santa Gallo (Bolivar), both
departments located in the north of the country, according to
reports from the Caracol Television Channel.
</P>
<P>
The ELN seeks to hold in the demilitarized zone what it defines
as a National Convention for the peace of the country, immersed in
an armed conflict for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement with the government follows the release by the
ELN of five crew members and three passengers of an Avianca
airliner hijacked more than one year ago by this guerrilla group,
and the announcement of an Easter truce.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian ambassador to Cuba and government negotiator with
the ELN, Julio Londono Paredes, met Wednesday with Colombian
President Andres Pastrana to analyze a proposal from the guerrilla
group.
</P>
<P>
The possible establishment of a demilitarized zone to pave the
way for the peace process with the ELN has provoked protests from
the heads of the peasant communities in the south of Bolivar, and
even from the mayors.
</P>
<P>
Monte Cristo municipality mayor Jesus Barragan revealed that
Santa Rosa is prepared to reject the guerrillas and the
paramilitary alike, since it is fed up with both.
</P>
<P>
He warned the government that it should consult the matter with
the local communities before arriving at any agreement with the
ELN, or else the people would abandon Monte Cristo.
</P>
<P>
The south of Bolivar is a zone disputed by the ELN and the
paramilitary groups, and for this cause the local peasants have
suffered an escalation of violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Refuses to Use Eritrean Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi reiterated here on Thursday that his country would
not use Eritrean ports for the shipment of food aid to the drought
victims.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Meles said that it would take
at least two months to rehabilitate Eritrean ports of Assab and
Massawa, which had been out of operations for long period.
</P>
<P>
It would be unthinkable to ferry relief food via Eritrean
ports, as they are full of soldiers and mines, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrean have been at war since May 1998 over
border dispute. Ethiopia used to make use of Eritrean ports for
imports and exports before the war erupted.
</P>
<P>
Meles also accused the Eritrean government of having looted
more than 70, 000 tons of relief assistance destined for Ethiopia
in the past.
</P>
<P>
Meles said the combined capacity of Djibouti port and the
Somali port of Berbera was big enough to deal with Ethiopia's
monthly relief food requirement of 175,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the pressure put by some foreign countries and
 organizations on Ethiopia to use the Eritrean ports was unjust
and politically motivated and aimed at complicating relief
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
