<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Elian Should Be Reunited With Father Promptly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Clinton told reporters at the White House that there is "no
conceivable argument" to keep Elian and his father apart after a
federal appeals court ruled the boy cannot leave the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I think he should be reunited with his son. That is the law
and the main argument of the family in Miami for not doing so has
now been removed," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
asked Americans to write to Clinton and Attorney General Janet
Reno to pressure them to reunite him with Elian.
</P>
<P>
"The court has now said he shouldn't go back to Cuba. The
Justice Department agrees with that and he (the father) has agreed
to that so there now is no conceivable argument for his not being
able to be reunited with his son," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
issued an order that keeps Elian in the United States pending an
appeal for an asylum filed by the relatives in Miami for the boy.
</P>
<P>
Reno has repeatedly insisted that the boy should be returned to
his father. On Wednesday, she said that the Justice Department
will abide by the appeals court rule over the case of Elian
Gonzalez, but stressed that the rule will not prevent the
government from transferring the six-year-old Cuban boy to his
father.
</P>
<P>
"The immigration laws clearly call for a child to be placed in
the care of a parent, in preference to a more distant relative,
while the child's immigration status is being resolved," Reno told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The court panel decided to bar anyone from attempting to remove
the Cuban shipwreck survivor from the country, extending the
injunction issued last week.
</P>
<P>
The panel announced that they recognized the government's
authority over immigration matters, but adding that "we fail to
see how an injunction in the case infringes upon the congressional
power."
</P>
<P>
"The 11th Circuit's order, as I say, prevents him from leaving
the country while the appeal is pending. We will abide by that,"
Reno said.
</P>
<P>
However, she made it clear that the court rule "does not
preclude me from placing Elian in his father's care while he is in
the United States."
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 near a shipwreck after his
mother and 10 others were killed when their boat capsized in the
sea off Florida and later was sent to his relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
The appeals court order temporarily blocked anyone from taking
Elian out of the country until it decides whether to hear the
asylum claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000420.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Begins Talks with Arafat over Mideast peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday expressed his hope that Israel and the Palestinians could
bridge their differences so that a framework agreement could be
reached in May, thus smoothing the way for a final agreement in
September.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a photo session with Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat, who arrived earlier in the day for talks, at the White
House, Clinton said the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations "reached
a very serious time in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
President Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak "have
set for themselves an ambitious timetable to reach a framework
agreement as soon as they can and then a final agreement by the
middle of September. So we are working hard on it, and I think we'
ll get some things done today," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this afternoon, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
met Arafat at her Georgetown residence. State Department spokesman
James Rubin did not disclose anything about their discussions at a
regular briefing, saying he was not aware of any new U.S. ideas
being presented, but he did not rule out the possibility of "
creative suggestions" at some points.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the United States was prepared to play a more
active role in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations as the
September deadline for a final status agreement was drawing nearer.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone agreed that we will play a more involved role by
being at the table, trying to be creative, trying to help each
side figure out what its needs are," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would do whatever he could to help bridge the
gap between Israel and the Palestinians over a series of issues,
like the borders, Jerusalem, refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Clinton
wanted to use the face-to-face talks to make sure what Washington
could do to help Israeli-Palestinian negotiations move toward a
framework agreement and then a final status agreement.
</P>
<P>
"I think the president thought it would be useful and effective
to use this time to meet directly to see what we can do to keep
these (talks) on track," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Clinton held talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to try to renew momentum in the negotiations between Israel
and the Palestinians as the target date for a framework agreement
in May is drawing nearer while gaps still remained wide between
the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said both Israelis and Palestinians were facing very
difficult issues, saying that "they have a very tight time line."
</P>
<P>
The second round of Bolling Air Force Base negotiations between
Israeli and the Palestinian delegations ended last weekend with an
exchange of position papers on the framework agreement but no
evidence of substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials say that Washington is trying to help bridge the
gaps but it has not reached the stage of proposing compromises.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said on Monday that he would take some "positive ideas"
to the White House, and considered his trip to Washington "a
crucial and basic step to push the peace process forward."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian cabinet minister Hassan Asfour on Tuesday held out
little hope for a breakthrough when Arafat meets Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We have nothing new to add, he said. "There is no place for
more flexibility. We were the party which made a historical
concession in 1993 and not the Israelis."
</P>
<P>
1993 was the year of the Oslo accords between Israel and the
PLO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
